<HEADLINE> Drug Arrests of Juveniles Increase Sharply in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The number of juveniles
charged with narcotics-related crimes across the United States has
more than doubled since the beginning of the decade, the Federal
Investigation Bureau (FBI) said.
</P>
<P>
The number of arrests has jumped from 64,740 in 1990 to 147,107
by 1995.
</P>
<P>
The capital Washington area was among the regions with greatest
increase in the arrests. In Fairfax County, the number of
juveniles charged with drug violations last year was more than
seven times more than five years ago, The Washington Post quoted
FBI as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, in Loudoun County, the number of youths arrested in
1995 was nearly 12 times the number at the beginning of the
decade. Some other areas, such as Arlington, Montgomery and Prince
George's counties, in the Washington area also have the number
doubled or nearly doubled since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, 40 percent of juveniles convicted of serious
crimes in Ohio had drug abuse problems, but today, the percentage
has risen to 70.
</P>
<P>
About 16 percent of juveniles arrestees tested positive for
drug use in 1990 in the District of Columbia, but it rose to 55
percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the number of juveniles being arrested for
drug-related crime was a result of the increase in drug use among
youths.
</P>
<P>
A recently published survey showed that drug use among eighth
graders has more than doubled since 1991, from 11 percent to 24
percent. Among the 10th graders,it has risen from 20 percent to 38
percent. And for 12th graders it has risen from 27 percent to 40
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
