<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India Agree to Release Detained Fishermen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and India have
agreed to mutually release detained fishermen, a spokesman from
Pakistan's Foreign Ministry said here today.
</P>
<P>
During his weekly press briefing, the spokesman said Pakistan
and India have also recognized the need to have an understanding
to free the civilian detainees held by both sides on humanitarian
grounds.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed that these issues should be dealt at a
humanitarian level and not be affected by political
considerations, he added.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at an informal meeting between
Pakistani caretaker Foreign Minister Yaqub Khan and his Indian
counterpart I.K. Gujral during the recent ministerial meeting of
the South Asian Association of Regional Cooperation held in New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman did not give the number of the detained
fishermen and civilian detainees held in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Yaqub Khan and I.K. Gujral felt that
"something should be done to resume the dialogue between the two
countries," the spokesman said,
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that the Kashmir issue should form main
part of the agenda whenever there are talks between India and
Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
