<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Central Bank Chief Warns of Rate Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The chief of the British
central bank has warned of a rise in interest rates early next
year to counter inflation.
</P>
<P>
As the British economy has enjoyed a fairly strong recovery,
interest rates should be further raised to slow down the growth,
Bank of England Governor Eddie George said in an interview
published here today.
</P>
<P>
"For the fifth consecutive year we are seeing solid growth of
the economy," George told the French newspaper, Le Figaro. "In
order to contain this growth, it will be necessary, sooner or
later, to increase interest rates," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative government, facing strong challenge by the
Labor Party in the general elections scheduled for next May, is
anxious to avoid raising rates as it would anger millions of
voters who need home loans.
</P>
<P>
The Tory party, led by John Major, lost its overall majority in
parliament last week. Opinion polls now gave Labor a comfortable
lead.
</P>
<P>
The basic interest rates were raised by a quarter point to 6
percent on October 30, when Chancellor of the Exchequer (finance
minister) Kenneth Clarke yielded to pressure from the central bank
to cool down the buoyant economy and meet the government's target
of 2.5 percent inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the bank's quarterly inflation report said that
further rises would be necessary before the elections. The remark
was echoed by the Confederation of British Industry.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the single European currency to be introduced in
1999, George said difference among European Union (EU) member
states over interest rates could cause tension which could weaken
the currency Euro.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem lies in the fact that some EU countries
with weaker economy, in a bid to join the monetary union in the
first wave, are trying every means to meet the strict qualifying
criteria for the common currency.
</P>
<P>
George warned against such moves and said, "The risks that
things could go wrong are real and considerable."
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that his remarks are likely to further
press Clarke, enthusiastic supporter for Britain's participation
in the monetary union in the first batch in 1999, to give in to
other Cabinet members and the Tory party who oppose Britain's
active engagement in the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
