<HEADLINE> Iraq to Buy Egyptian Goods With Oil Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Iraq will buy at least 21
million U.S. dollars worth of Egyptian vegetable oil and soap in
one of its first purchases of food and other daily necessities
since resuming oil exports recently.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) today reported that
the Egyptian Holding Company for Food Industries has just
concluded a deal on providing Iraq with the edible oil.
</P>
<P>
The 8 million U.S. dollar deal, which is to be signed next
week, will bring the total sum of agreements between Egypt and
Iraq up to 21 million dollars, the MENA quoted a business source
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The company signed two days ago a 13-million-dollar deal to
export vegetable oil and soap to Iraq under the United Nations
oil-for-food agreement.
</P>
<P>
So far, 29 countries and regions have offered to sell food and
medicine to Baghdad, following the six years of international
embargo since the 1990-1991 Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
It has made 13 contracts with about 20 companies the world
over for exporting oil under the deal with the United Nations,
which allows Iraq to export 2 billion dollars worth of oil in six
months to help alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will use 1.2 billion dollars to purchase food, medicine
and other daily necessities, which is much lesser than the 8
billion dollars it used to buy food and medicine every year
before the U.N. imposed sanctions in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has reappeared as a marketing force in the oil-rich Gulf
after exporting two supertankers from its Mina al-Bakr terminal
since the deal took effect on December 10.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's first customers in the Gulf are U.S. firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
