<HEADLINE> US Charged with Interference in Singapore's Domestic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Singapore today charged the
United States with interfering in Singapore's domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
"The statement of the US State Department press officer on the
conduct of the election campaign in Singapore is an undisguised
interference in Singapore's domestic politics," a spokesman of the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to a local television report, a US State Department
press officer said in Washington on Wednesday that the candidates
of the ruling People's Action Party (PAP), including Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong, had warned that constituencies that elect
opposition candidates would receive low priority in their house
upgrading.
</P>
<P>
The press officer said that the United States believed voters
everywhere should be able to vote without fear of repercussions
from the government.
</P>
<P>
Goh said today that the comments were totally absurd. "I was
furious, flabbergasted, floored. This is a local election and what
we offer the people as a program is no different from what any
candidate anywhere else will offer their electorate," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry spokesman noted that this is not the first
time the US officials have tried to influence domestic politics in
Singapore. In 1988 the Singapore government protested to the US
government over the improper behavior of a diplomat of the US
Embassy for interfering in the domestic politics of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"In the US, the use of political advertisements to scare voters
with the prospect of losing health and welfare entitlements if
they should vote for the wrong party has been honed to a fine art.
Singapore does no more than the same thing, but without political
advertisements," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore has not commented on the conduct of elections in the
US. American election campaigns will provide endless opportunities
for comment should the Singapore government choose to so comment.
But this is not how countries should conduct relations with each
other. We expect US officials to accord us the same courtesy," the
spokesman stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
