<HEADLINE> Cambodia to Tighten Control on Illegal Timber Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 26 (Xinhua)-- Cambodia will impose a ban
on log and timber export, effective from 1997, in a bid to halt
illegal trade activities.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers has approved a clear-cut forest policy
and tougher measures to curb illegal logging and forest business
activities across the country, according to a communique issued
today
</P>
<P>
The ban on all log and timber export is a response to rampant
illegal forest businesses in the nation.
</P>
<P>
Any timber export without prior government approval in the
future will be seen as an infringement of the law of Cambodia, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The ministries of Finance, Defense, Interior, Agriculture,
Environment, Commerce and General Chief of Staff of the Royal
Cambodian Armed Forces will be responsible for the implementation
of the ban.
</P>
<P>
The government has ordered regular troops to replace armed
units of forest companies to handle matters of security. The
company-owned security teams will be disbanded completely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
