<HEADLINE> SAARC Tourism Council Meeting Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 26 (Xinhua) -- A two-day meeting of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) Tourism
Council opened here this evening with a view to finding the
priorities and needs in the region's tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the meeting, Nepali Prime Minister Sher Bahadur
Deuba said that the growth of tourism within the South Asia region
will benefit all the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Stating that tourism is in the priority list of the Nepali
government, Deuba called on participants of the meeting to explore
the possibility of investing in the tourism sector in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Representatives including government officials and businessmen
involved in tourism from all the seven SAARC members --
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka -- are taking part in the meeting, which is the last of a
series of meetings held by the council after it was formed last
June.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC Tourism Council, currently chaired by Nepal and run
by a governing board with five representatives from each member
countries, aims to contribute to the economic growth of the region
through tourism development by promoting regional cooperation,
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
A SAARC Tourism Declaration, which will outline future tasks
for each country in the region on tourism cooperation, is expected
to be finalized and adopted at the end of the meeting, they said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
