<HEADLINE> S. Africa Cuts Hospital Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 26 (Xinhua) -- An acute shortage of
professional staff has forced the health authorities in Gauteng
Province of South Africa to cut services at Kemptong Park
Hospital, the South African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kemptong Park Hospital, one of the major hospitals in
Johannesburg, will only offer services for out-patients and
antenatal women as of January 1, 1997, the report quoted a
statement by the Gauteng Health Department as saying.
</P>
<P>
The municipal hospital, assessed as "non-cost effective" due
to low utilization, is one of the three hospitals in Gauteng
Province that are proposed for closure in terms of the Health
Department's structural transformation plan.
</P>
<P>
However, Deputy Director-General of the Gauteng Health
Department Eric Buch said: "the reason to cut services at Kempton
Part Hospital is that staffing levels at this hospital have
dropped so low that it is impossible to keep a full range of
hospital services going".
</P>
<P>
Buch said a suggestion that Kempton Park Hospital should
become a joint private-public sector venture is under serious
consideration by the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts have noticed that South Africa has been making
efforts to carry out structural transformation in the medical
care field ever since the abolition of apartheid in 1994 in hope
to improve the public health.
</P>
<P>
Under new regulations made by the Pretoria government,
hospitals, which used to serve the white people before 1994, must
be open to the blacks.
</P>
<P>
An informed source, who asked not to be identified, said that
thanks to the ongoing social transformation, the black people have
been able to enjoy low-price medical services for more than two
years.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the medical change has also led to dramatic
subsidy-cut by the government, thus having remarkably restrained
income of the white medical staff.
</P>
<P>
"Many doctors and nurses have either gone abroad or shifted
to private clinics to make a good living," the source said.
</P>
<P>
Kempton Park Hospital is apparently one of the hospitals that
are suffering most from the shortage of doctors and nurses, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
