<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Puts Education, Science on Top Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
decided to give education and science top priority in the process
of national industrialization and modernization, a communique said
today.
</P>
<P>
The government will attach importance to strategies aimed at
training personnel, developing talents, mobilizing human resources
and raising the people's education level with an eye on the coming
century, said the communique released at the second plenum of the
eighth central committee of the ruling Vietnamese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
It urged the whole nation to tap the scientific and
technological potential and train a contingent of qualified cadres
and skilled workers in a bid to meet the need of the country's
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The communique said those in the educational sector should
introduce management reform and restore order and discipline, and
work out a practical strategy to develop national education.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech at the meeting, Party General Secretary Do
Muoi called on party committees and authorities at different
levels and mass organizations to give more attention to the
development of education and training, as well as science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed ways to fight against corruption and
squandering, curb deficit and mobilize domestic sources to
develop national infrastructure and technical facilities.
</P>
<P>
"The Resolutions on Development Strategies for Education and
Training, and for Science and Technology to the Year 2000" were
discussed and passed at the party's meeting held from December 16
to 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
