<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBK Introduces New Trading System for Treasury  Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya
(CBK) is scheduled to introduce a new trading system for the
auction of Treasury bills, according to a Daily Nation report
today.
</P>
<P>
The first auction under the new system named as the Central
Depository System (CDS) will be held on January 2 next year, the
paper quoted Chief Banking Manager Reuben Marambii as saying.
</P>
<P>
The CDS is an electronic and paperless trading system which
works through immobilizing securities and financial instruments
by placing them in a centralized location.
</P>
<P>
Once the system is in place, investors will be able to buy and
sell financial instruments without the need to present physical
proof of ownership as the transfer of title will be linked to the
payment of cash electronically.
</P>
<P>
According to a recently-held seminar on the CDS, the new
system will reduce cost by up to 50 percent while considerably
increasing the volumes of transactions.
</P>
<P>
Marambii disclosed that under the new system, a minimum one
million Kenyan Shillings (about 18,000 U.S. Dollars) investment
is allowed to participate in the auction.
</P>
<P>
Investors of less than this amount can place their investments
in the new one-year floating bond facility for a minimum of
10,000 Shillings or purchase T-bills in denominations of 50,000
Shillings in the secondary market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
