<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Wins BBC's Personality of Year Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John
Major on Thursday won the BBC Today programme's annual Personality
of the Year poll with 23 percent of the 140,000 votes cast,
according to a BBC television report today.
</P>
<P>
In second place was Lisa Potts, a Wolverhampton nursery nurse
who saved her children from a machete attack.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the poll was surrounded by controversy this
year after Tony Blair, the main opposition Labor Party leader, was
disqualified after a party official had urged Labor supporters to
vote for him.
</P>
<P>
Although the procedures were tightened, the poll conducted by
telephone remained open to manipulation.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's percentage was reduced after attempts at
multiple calls for him, but he was still the clear winner after
being the runner-up for two years.
</P>
<P>
The poll was dominated between 1982 and 1990 by Mrs Thatcher
who won every year except for 1985. And after 1990, the award was
rested for four years and was revived in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Last year it was won by headteacher Philip Lawrence who was
stabbed to death outside his west London school while attempting
to protect a pupil.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
