<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Offers $30.4 Mln Credit for Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of an Interim Trust Fund (ITF) credit
equivalent to some 30.4 million U.S. dollars for the Disease
Control and Health Development Project in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at the control of preventable diseases and
by rehabilitating health system infrastructure to improve the
delivery of basic health services.
</P>
<P>
The estimated total cost of the project is some 35.6 million
dollars. In addition to the ITF credit, the Cambodian government
will contribute the remaining 5.2 million dollars for the project.
</P>
<P>
The ITF was created by the World Bank to bridge the
International Development Association (IDA) funding gap for the
fiscal year 1997 created by the absence of new funding from the
United States for FY97. The U.S. announced they would not be
making a contribution to the ITF, but wanted to clear their
arrears to IDA, the World Bank's concessionary lending arm for
developing countries. Contribution from donors other than the
United States to the ITF are expected to exceed 3 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
