<HEADLINE> Arafat Expects Hebron Accord to Be Reached </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Authority (PA)
President Yasser Arafat said today that an agreement on partial
Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank city of Hebron will
be concluded at last either next Monday or Tuesday, reported
Israel Television.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the prediction in Ramallah, the West Bank, when he
was briefing the 88-member legislative Palestinian Council on
details of an emerging accord.
</P>
<P>
He said that the agreement still under negotiations will not
be different from the accord signed with the previous Israeli
Labor government.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
had given him a detailed timetable on further army pullout from
the West Bank. The first will take place six weeks after the
Hebron deal is signed.
</P>
<P>
In nearby Jerusalem, meanwhile, Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators were thrashing out the final details. The remaining
issues include a buffer zone separating Jewish settlers from
Palestinian residents in the city, and the types of weapons
allowed for the Palestinian police in the city.
</P>
<P>
Some 450 Jewish settlers living among 120,000 Palestinians in
Hebron, the last West Bank city still under Israeli occupation.
</P>
</TEXT>
