<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Step up Efforts to Develop Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Tourist
Board (TTB) will inject large sum into the tourism sector to
attract more tourists between now and the year 2005 through a
strong strategy worked out by it.
</P>
<P>
TTB Managing Director Credo Sinyangwe said today that the laid
down strategy would be financed by the World Bank and the
European Union under a Five-Year Tourism Infrastructure Project
and a 10-Year Integrated Tourism Master Plan respectively.
</P>
<P>
He told the tomorrow published Daily News paper here that the
World Bank is expected soon to disburse 100 million U.S. Dollars
for the five-year project.
</P>
<P>
He did not disclose the amount to be released by the European
Union, and only said both plans are underway. Sinyangwe said by
the year 2000, it is expected that the infrastructure
improvements would be completed.
</P>
<P>
He further said by the year 2005, it is projected that a total
of 400 million U.S. Dollars would have been invested in tourism,
approximatedly two-thirds of those invested by the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
The TTB boss said by the year 2000, tourist arrivals would
surpass 500,000 per annum and the rate of their expenditures in
the country was expected to rise accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Sinyangwe said apart from marketing the tourist attraction
centers in the North and Southern part, the board is also now
striving to market the waters of the Great Lakes for sports.
</P>
<P>
He said since its inception of the TTB two years ago, the
board has recorded sound developments in terms of income
earnings. He said the TTB earned 258.15 million Dollars in 1995
compared to 146.84 million U.S. Dollars earned in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The TTB boss said the tourist traffic has increased from
230,000 in 1995 to 293,000 last year, adding that the income
earnings increased by 75 percent whereas tourist flow went up by
27.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
