<HEADLINE> Kenya, Tanzania to Curb Illegal Refugee Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Kenya and
Tanzania have tightened security along their common border to
stop illegal entry of refugees, the Kenya News Agency report
today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting held today at the border town of Sirare in
Tanzania, both sides said they are resolved to take stringent
measures to curb the movement of refugees from Tanzania to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The meeting called on the border police to be vigilant while
patroling along the major roads to curb any influx of refugees.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 21 Rwandan refugees from camps in
northwestern Tanzania were arrested by Tanzanian border police on
December 24 as they attempted to cross the border into Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government has ordered a return of 540,000
Rwandan refugees to their home before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 300,000 have returned from Tanzania to
Rwanda and some 200 Rwandan refugees have reportedly been
arrested and accused of genocide after returning home from
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
As a result, former government officials, Hutu extremist
militias and former soldiers who fled to Tanzania as refugees
were quoted as saying that they would rather face the
International Tribunal for Rwanda than be returned to their
homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
