<HEADLINE> Aidid Urges Ethiopian Troops to Withdraw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Somali faction leader
Hussein Mohamed Aidid today accused Ethiopian forces of invading
into the Southwestern Gedo region of Somalia and urged them to
withdraw immediately and unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Aidid described the Ethiopian "aggression as
unacceptable", saying although his government is opposed to any
group destabilizing the security of any of the neighboring
countries, referring to the Al-Itihad Moslem fundamentalists in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Ethiopian troops have in the past week crossed
into Somalia 20 kilometers and taken the border town of Dolow in
pursuit of Moslem extremists.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid also said an official letter has been sent to
the government of Ethiopia over the matter concerned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the situation at the war ravaged border between
Somalia and Ethiopia remains calm for the second day today
following simultaneous clashes that occurred between the forces
of Ethiopia and those of the Islamic extremist group of Al-Itihad
in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Ali Abdi, Deputy Chairman of the Somali National Front
(SNF) of Marehan clan which controls Gedo region, admitted for
the first time that his militiamen are now fighting against the
"Ethiopian aggressors".
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists through the VHF radio in the border
town of Bulo Hawo, he accused Ethiopian troops of abducting five
Somali farmers and businessmen from the outskirts of Bulo Hawo,
including a former Somali policeman.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the area almost all women and
children have been evacuated from the town for fear of fighting.
</P>
<P>
Abdi admitted that the incursion by the Ethiopians has split
the leadership of his faction since chairman of SNF General Omar
Haji Masalle supports what he called the eradication of Moslem
extremists from the region by the Ethiopian forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
