<HEADLINE> China Spells Out New Measures for Development of Coal Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Minister of Coal
Industry Wang Senhao said today that China will realize the goal
of producing 1.45 billion tons of coal annually by the year 2000
by adopting new measures.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a national meeting on coal industry in Zhengzhou,
capital of central China's Henan Province, the minister said that
in the years to come China will succeed in the building of seven
large mines, including Pingshuo Open-Cut Mine in north China's
Shanxi Province and Shenfu Open-Cut Mine in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Locally-owned mines will also accelerate the construction of 15
bases for production of open-market coal, while a good job must
also be done in the construction of 100 major coal production
counties to advance the upgrading of rural and township-owned coal
mines.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that his ministry would continue to list 300
large projects, involving coal mine construction and sideline
production of coal mines, to seek overseas cooperation and adopt
more open policies to create a broad investment arena for overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
According to the coal minister, the coal industrial sector has
asked 16 large coal mines and 39 coal-burning thermal power
plants, as well as 180 sideline production and comprehensive
development projects, to seek cooperation and attract overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
The high-ranking Chinese official noted that currently China
should first guarantee the implementation of strategic startup
programs in the coal industry, with the focus going to making a
success of building pit power stations, using pipelines to
transmit coal, developing coal gas and developing clean coal
technology.
</P>
<P>
Different coal mines are also being urged to build power
plants, coking and coal-chemical factories, to fully develop and
utilize regenerated mineral resources, while trying hard to adjust
industrial structures, and to conduct comprehensive development
and sideline production businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
