<HEADLINE> New Caledonians Agree on 'Shared Sovereignty' With France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The two major political rival
parties in the French Pacific territory of New Caledonia today
agreed to negotiate for a "shared sovereignty" with France, Agence
France Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The pro-independence movement, Kanak Nationalist Socialist
Liberation Front (FLNKS), and the pro-French Rally for Caledonia
in the Republic (RPCR), used the same terms in respective
declarations made at the local congress.
</P>
<P>
An AFP report said the declarations could mean a new start of
talks on the future of the colony after a long-time deadlock
between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed the Matignon Accords with France in 1988,
which called for the stop of violence on the island and a
referendum in 1998 on the future of the colony.
</P>
<P>
"A negotiated solution will pave the way after 1998 to shared
sovereignty with France," said FLNKS President Rock Wamytan.
</P>
<P>
Congress President Pierre Frogier, who is from RPCR, said that
new agreements, which are expected by the end of 1997 between
France, the FLNKS and RPCR, could allow the colony to have
political stability for at least 24 years, or four terms of the
local congress.
</P>
<P>
Both Wamytan and Frogier described the independence process of
the island as "irreversible."
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between France, the FLNKS and RPCR came to a halt
in April last year after the FLNKS pulled out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
