<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Test New Planes Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine is scheduled to carry out
the test flights early next year of the prototype An-70 and An-140
airplanes coming out of the assembly line on December 23.
</P>
<P>
Both planes are designed by Antonov Aviation Designing Bureau
in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
An-70, a wide-bodied military transport plane, can fly 5,000
kilometers nonstop with 30 tons of cargoes, at a cruising speed of
750 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
It is claimed to be capable of not only replacing the old
military transport plane An-12, but also carrying out specialized
missions of the An-76 civil planes.
</P>
<P>
Jointly made by Ukraine, Russia and Uzbekistan, An-70 is
installed with four new turboprops, which will use 20 to 30
percent less fuel than similar planes.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian experts claimed that An-70's outstanding performance
could counter any competition from other countries in next 10
years. They added that it could be a substitute to the U.S. C-130
transport plane, designed by Lockheed Martin 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
An-140 is a short-range passenger aircraft designed to
eventually replace the renewed An-24. In the former Soviet Union,
about 40 percent of passenger planes were An-24.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that An-140 is much more superior to An-24 in all
aspects. It can save fuel by up to 50 percent, and its take-off
distance is much shorter.
</P>
<P>
Antonov Aviation Designing Bureau estimated that the potential
sales of An-140 can reach 600 to 800 planes, mostly to the CIS
countries.
</P>
<P>
Although the government hails the successes of the new planes
as miracles, An-70 still faces much criticism.
</P>
<P>
Vitaly Konov, a former chief engineer at the Antonov Aviation
Designing Bureau, said An-70's control system has adopted a
Russian electronic system far below international standards.
</P>
<P>
"Due to its low performance, unreliable equipment and engine,
the potential buyer of An-70 can only be Russia," said Konov, who
has worked with the designing bureau for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
The government is spending huge money on an unrealistic
project, Konov said. "The future of Ukraine's aviation industry
lies not in heavy planes, but in multi-purpose light aircraft for
agriculture."
</P>
<P>
He expressed doubts whether next year's test flight could be
successful, saying that the internal management at the designing
bureau has become so messy that an outsider will never believe
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
