<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> b d e 2269 C-China-Rural-Funds China to Rectify Rampant Rural Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese authorities will take
measures in 1997 to rectify the mushrooming of unlicensed
so-called rural cooperative funds across the country to maintain a
stable economic and social order in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Duan Xiaoxing, Deputy Director of State
Council Inter-Department Coordinative Group for Rural Financial
Reforms, in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The rural financing bodies have appeared up since the early 80s
when the responsibility system was widely adopted by farmers with
the abandoning of the people's commune system, according to Duan.
</P>
<P>
These funds were set up by local governments in town and
township levels, and were first defined as financing organizations
only for the purpose of developing agricultural development and
making no profits, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
None of them have been granted licenses to do any kinds of
money-making businesses, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, due to its rapid expansion and ignorance by
the local authorities, most of the rural funds have turned away
from their original targets, and are now engaged in banking
businesses like handling deposits and loans.
</P>
<P>
The illegal banking activities have led to many problems and a
large number of the funds are losing money, which has brought
losses for stake-holders of the funds. This is hampering local
agricultural production and social stability.
</P>
<P>
The official declined to disclose the number of the funds and
the amount of money involved, but he said the numbers were huge,
and the rectification should be implemented without any delay and
hesitation.
</P>
<P>
The rectification will be carried out strictly in line with the
Comments on Rectification of Rural Cooperative Funds, jointly
issued by People's Bank of China and Ministry of Agriculture, Duan
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the funds will be first registered, and then be
rectified in a classified way, noting that those that have
violated the law will have to stop their operations, and those
that meet the rules will be standardized in accordance with the
newly-issued "Regulations on Administration of Rural Cooperative
Funds".
</P>
<P>
"It will be a very tough job," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
