<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria's Antiquities Survive Strong Tremor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The antiquities in central
Syrian Palmyra have survived a strong earthquake this week.
</P>
<P>
Khalid al Asaad, director of antiquities in Palmyra district,
said that Tuesday's tremor has caused no negative effects on the
ancient city monuments while the antiquity colonnades as well as
other sites remain intact, according to the Syrian News Agency
today.
</P>
<P>
The tremor took place 16 minutes after midnight Tuesday,
registering 5.3 degrees on the Richter scale. It lasted 15
seconds. It is believed that an earthquake above five degree on
the Richter scale can cause severe damage.
</P>
<P>
Al Asaad added that field surveys proved that no cracks had
been detected on Palmyra antiquities.
</P>
<P>
Palmyra is situated in the central part of Syria, some 235
kilometers northeast of Damascus, capital of the country. It
used to be a prosperous city during the second and third
centuries, being the pass as well as cross-roads between the East
and the West.
</P>
<P>
The ancient city has a host of antiquities, including ancient
temples, colonnades, arches, utilities, a theater, a citadel,
baths, walls, statues and beautiful inscriptions, which enjoy
world-wide fame.
</P>
<P>
The antiquities in Palmyra cover an area of six square
kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
