<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Lawmaker Calling for Solutions to Agricultural Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- In a year that has seen a
record crop harvest, a top Chinese legislator today called for
more money to be poured into agriculture and the lightening of
burdens on farmers.
</P>
<P>
"Ministries and localities must discuss and implement measures
to assure that there are enough agricultural funds, streamlining
circulation of farm produce, protecting limited farmland and
lessening the added burden on farmers," said Buhe, vice-chairman
of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
His call came in an address in Beijing to the NPC's Agriculture
Law enforcement groups who have returned from Shaanxi, Henan,
Anhui and Zhejiang provinces.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, who also joined one of the enforcement groups, said that
in general the law's implementation has been better year by year.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that more funds have been invested in agriculture,
with local heads seeming to be more law-minded.
</P>
<P>
The price hikes on grain procurement in recent years have also
spurred farmers to plant and purvey farm produce.
</P>
<P>
Various levels of the government are underscoring issues of
irrational loads on farmers, accounting for 70 percent of China's
population, while most localities comply with the five percent
burden ceiling, a limitation set by the central government which
outlaws money collected of more than five percent of farmers' net
income in the previous years, he added.
</P>
<P>
China has set harvest record in two straight years. An
abundance of by-products, rapid flourishing of township
enterprises and farmers' increasing incomes, all this are largely
attributed to the implementation of the agriculture law, Buhe said.
</P>
<P>
Despite some advances in the basic sector, he still pointed out
problems which he claimed perplexed the most significant sector.
</P>
<P>
They are lack of added investment in agriculture, particularly
in some poverty-stricken areas; underdeveloped markets of some
farm produce, especially for grain and cotton; lack of strict
management to protect farmland; rebounding of farmers' extra
economic loads and unreasonable taxation in a few areas; and a
lack of enough legislation on agriculture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
