<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The prices for petrol,
diesel and paraffin will be up throughout South Africa following
the rise of prices for petroleum goods in the international
market, a statement by the Central Energy Fund (CEF) said today.
</P>
<P>
The petrol price will rise by three cents a liter as of
January 1 next year while the price of diesel will be up by four
cents a liter.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the price-up is that the prices for petroleum
goods, such as gasoline, diesel and paraffin, in the
international market increased in late November, the CEF said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which fell into a retrenchment period in 1996,
has announced several pieces of price-up information before the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Telecommunications Company, suffering from
financial constraint, said early December it would rise telephone
fees by 28 percent beginning from mid-January next year.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources, who asked not to be identified, said other
state-owned industrial giants like Postal Services, National
Airlines and Transportation Network, which have been suggested by
experts to become private ones due to sharp subsidy-cuts by the
government, are also planning to charge more money for their
products and services in the near future. 
