<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Needs to Increase Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines needs to raise
annual investments in the infrastructure sector to 5.8 billion
U.S. dollars to sustain its economic growth, a senior official of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The estimated 2.9 billion U.S. dollars poured into the sector
every year was insufficient to upgrade existing infrastructure in
the country, said David Nellor, IMF representative to Manila.
</P>
<P>
Based on IMF estimates, the Philippines allots, on the average,
2.8 percent of total capital expenditures or about 268 U.S. dollar
of per capita income to infrastructure, he said.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Thailand, whose economy grows at an average rate
of 8 to 9 percent, invests 3.9 percent of its total capital
expenditures or about 757 U.S. dollars of per capita income in the
sector.
</P>
<P>
To clear "infrastructure bottlenecks" and lure more foreign
capital into the sector, the Philippine government has in recent
years drawn up and carried out innovative schemes such as the
build-operate-transfer and build-own-operate arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Manila also hopes to improve its energy, telecommunications and
transportation infrastructure through regional trading
arrangements such as the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
and the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth of foreign investments was still influenced
by the inadequate infrastructure across the country.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, Nellor urged the Philippine government
to pursue policy and structural reforms despite fierce opposition
from non-governmental organizations and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government must ensure that fiscal
accounts are placed on a sound footing by completing the
comprehensive tax reform program and ensuring the passage of
legislation trimming down the size of bureaucracy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
