<HEADLINE> Strikers Not to Be Paid Under New Law in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Australian employees,
including Commonwealth public servants, taking part in industrial
action, will no longer be paid under a federal workplace law,
which will take effect on January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Federal Industrial Relations Minister Peter Reith said today
the Workplace Relations Act, passed by the Senate last month, made
payments to workers taking any form of industrial action illegal.
</P>
<P>
From now on, public servants who breached their agreements and
disrupted customer services would not be paid for the period they
failed to carry out duties, the minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the provisions would apply equally to federally-covered
public and private sectors, and it aimed to ensure that workers
and employers alike abide by their agreement obligations.
</P>
<P>
Reith said that while the new law provided for a right to
strike during negotiations for an agreement, employers should not
be forced to foot the bill for that industrial action.
</P>
<P>
It will also be illegal for unions and their members to make
claim for pay in respect of any period of industrial action or to
organize or threaten industrial action for such pay, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
