<HEADLINE> Spokesman on HK-Taiwan Air, Shipping Services After 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Air and shipping links between
Hong Kong and Taiwan after China's resumption of exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1, 1997 will be treated as
special regional routes under the "One China" principle.
</P>
<P>
The air and shipping services between the two places should be
handled in accordance with the principle of mutual benefits, said
a spokesman of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office and Taiwan
Affairs Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua in Beijing today, the spokesman
said that connections between the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region and Taiwan after 1997 is a special part of the
cross-straits relations.
</P>
<P>
In June of last year Vice-Premier Qian Qichen announced the
basic principles and policies of the Central People's Government
on handling relations between Hong Kong and Taiwan after 1997.
</P>
<P>
These principles and policies will help maintain the existing
non-governmental exchanges in economic, cultural, transportation
and other fields and personnel contacts between the two places on
the basis of the "One China" principle, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said arrangements have been made on air services beyond
1997 between Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
On shipping services, the spokesman said, vessels registered in
Taiwan, when entering Hong Kong ports, cannot show a flag that
would suggest a "two Chinas" situation.
</P>
<P>
While vessels registered in Hong Kong should be treated
according to the mutually beneficial principle when entering ports
in Taiwan, he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the normal operation of shipping
services between the two places under the "one China" principle
after 1997 will be helpful to their common economic development,
which is in the interests of compatriots both in Hong Kong and
Taiwan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
