<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Number of Slips Found in 1,700-year-old Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of bamboo
and wooden slips bearing 200,000 characters have been unearthed
from a 1,700-year-old well in a downtown area of Changsha city in
central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of the slips, surpassing the total number of
their kind ever found in the country, is one of the most
significant archaeological finds in China this century, according
to China's leading archaeologist at a press conference today in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He declared that this latest find is as important as the
discoveries of the world-renouned oracle bones and shells from the
Shang Dynasty (16-11th century BC) in central China's Henan
province and the Dunhuang documents in the Mogao Grottos in
northwest China's Gansu province.
</P>
<P>
The expert is Yu Weichao, Curator of the Museum of Chinese
History. He said that the well, three meters in diameter, was
actually a cellar which served as an archives of the Changsha
Prefecture under the Wu State (222-280) during the Three Kingdoms
Period (220-280).
</P>
<P>
The originally dry cellar was submerged in the past centuries
with the uplifting underground water level. This prevented the
slips from breaking up in a dry environment.
</P>
<P>
"The well-preserved slips will cover the shortage of historical
documents of the Three Kingdoms Period, a warring era," Yu
said. He made a special trip to Changsha to see the slips recently.
</P>
<P>
The slips are detailed records of the political, economic,
military, cultural and geographic situation of Changsha
prefecture, covering taxes, renting, registration, legal system,
administration positions, rites and storage.
</P>
