<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wine to Replace White Spirits in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Beijing may soon have much in
common with Bordeaux if supporters of fine wines have their way.
</P>
<P>
They want wine to replace the tradition toast of strong white
spirit as the favored tipple at banquets and gatherings.
</P>
<P>
Even the Chinese premier, Li Peng, has expressed the view that
wine should take over from traditional Chinese 'firewater' at
official functions.
</P>
<P>
Wine, it seems, will gradually replace white alcoholic spirits
in China as the country's material civilization and cultural and
ethical progress continues to improve.
</P>
<P>
Whether China ever rivals France as a nation of wine lovers
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
But Liu Changxi, Chairman of China Great Wall Wine Company
predicted the switch to wine at a seminar on wine culture in
China, which opened today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was jointly sponsored by four organizations,
including China Great Wall Wine Company, is the first of its kind
in China.
</P>
<P>
Consumption of spirits distilled from sorghum and maize during
festive seasons and at gatherings and banquets has long been a
tradition in China, especially in rural areas. The
strong 'firewater' is also viewed as a source of many serious
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, China has vigorously advocated "no
consumption of white spirit at official banquets, and starting a
common practise of saving grain".
</P>
<P>
Early this year, some 30 ministries and commissions of the
State Council issued a joint document calling for ending the
consumption of white spirit in all official banquets.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng has also put forward a proposal for
consuming more wine instead of white spirits during festive
seasons, or at gatherings.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and experts at the seminar believed that
China has great market potential for wine-making industries which
is also an efficient way to help poor areas quickly become
prosperous.
</P>
<P>
China set up its first winery in 1892 in Yantai, a coastal city
in east China's Shandong Province, and is now capable of producing
200,000 tons of wine a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
