<HEADLINE> Sasakawa Japan-China Friendship Fund Awards Chinese College Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen Chinese college
students each received 2,000 yuan (240 U.S. dollars) in
scholarships in Beijing today for their excellent performance in
learning Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The scholarships were provided by Sasakawa Japan-China
Friendship Fund, the largest fund involving in non-governmental
exchanges between China and Japan, with a total fund of 100
million yen (nearly one million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fund was founded in 1989 by the Japan Sasakawa Peace
Foundation (SPF) and the China Association for International
Friendly Contact (CAIFC).
</P>
<P>
Sasakawa Japan-China Friendship Fund has rewarded nearly 200
Chinese college students since it was founded last year. It has
set up special scholarships for Chinese students studying the
Japanese Language in six colleges and universities, including the
Shanghai Foreign Studies University, Sichuan Institute of Foreign
Languages, Northwest University, and Guangxi University.
</P>
<P>
The scholarship was designed for the training of "couriers" for
Sino-Japanese friendship in the 21st century, said Chen Hua,
vice-president of the CAIFC. He added that it would promote
bilateral understanding between young people of the two countries,
and help encourage the training of professionals majoring in the
Japanese language.
</P>
<P>
Sasakawa Japan-China Friendship Fund was founded in 1989 by the
Japan Sasakawa Peace Foundation (SPF) and the China Association
for International Friendly Contact (CAIFC).
</P>
<P>
More than 100 projects have been conducted between China and
Japan since then, such as personnel training, cultural exchanges,
research and study, staff exchanges, and the holding of
international seminars.
</P>
<P>
The Sasakawa Japan-China Friendship Fund, an essential channel
for Sino-Japanese friendly contact, has been playing an active
role in promoting bilateral understanding and cooperation in the
fields of politics, economy, culture, and education.
</P>
<P>
Gao Yuan, an official at CAIFC, said that the Sasakawa
Japan-China Friendship Fund has decided to include the Scholarship
as one of its 10-year projects in China. The scholarship would
cover major foreign languages institutes in China which open
courses of Japanese language.
</P>
<P>
The Scholarship would also give preference to colleges and
universities located in remote and inland areas of the
country. Sasakawa Japan-China Friendship Fund is also considering
sending some of the rewarded students on visits to Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
