<HEADLINE> Feature: President and Modern Literature Archives (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- China's President Jiang Zemin
has written an important chapter in the country's literary
heritage.
</P>
<P>
Jiang has been the driving force behind plans for the building
of the world's biggest archives in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The showpiece building will become the new home of hundreds of
thousands of original manuscripts, books, translations, letters,
diaries and even electronically produced materials of the
contemporary Chinese writers, the country's written and spoken
heritage captured on pages and in modern electronic media.
</P>
<P>
The foundation for the new Archives of Modern Chinese
Literature was laid in Beijing four weeks ago. Its launching was a
frequent subject of discussion among Chinese writers at the
recently-ended Fifth National Congress of the Chinese Writers
Association (CWA).
</P>
<P>
The largest literature construction project in China has won
accolades from China's top writer, Ba Jin, and also received great
interest of Chinese President and General Secretary of the Chinese
Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee, Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
The new archives will become the world's largest literature
archives after its completion. Its first-phase construction will
be finished by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The original and existing archives was initiated in 1981 by Ba
Jin, who is also CWA President. It opened to the public in 1985,
and has served as the state information and research center on
modern Chinese literature. It is located in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
It has collected 260,000 modern Chinese writers' manuscripts,
editions, translations, books, letters, diaries, as well as audio
and visual products.
</P>
<P>
The archives has set up special library collections of the
works of 33 top Chinese writers, which serves to demonstrate the
main achievements of modern Chinese literature, and to allow
research on the literary treasures.
</P>
<P>
However, as an increasing number of books and other literary
pieces are piling high at the archives, its space and facilities
can no longer meet the necessary standards to adequately preserve
the treasures.
</P>
<P>
The archives started to fall into its overcrowding position,
and this aroused wide concern among the country's writers.
</P>
<P>
Ba Jin, as the country's most famous writer, came forward and
urged the solving of the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Ba wrote to Jiang Zemin for help, saying "I feel
uneasy about the present difficulties the archives has
encountered. I wish the construction of a new archives to be put
onto the agenda and be approved."
</P>
<P>
He said in the letter, "This archives is my last piece of work
in my lifetime. But it is not for myself. I am willing to devote
all my remaining energy to the archives, as it has a bright future
and serves as a rich mine to show the refined souls of Chinese
people. I wish we have all the people's support and your
excellency's help."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: President and Modern Literature Archives (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xie Bingxin, Honorary President of the CWA, also wrote to a
leading figure of the State Council, saying China needs a new
archives to collect the literary treasures of modern China. He
said it will be a window to show China's profound culture and
literature.
</P>
<P>
Ba Jin's letter and the archives' difficulties have come to
Jiang's keen attention. According to his personal instructions, an
investigation team was sent to look into the matter, report to him
and offer preliminary proposals on a solution to the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In April 1993, Jiang wrote to officials of relevant
departments requiring more care about the construction of a
new archives.
</P>
<P>
He said: "All civilized countries in the world are always
willing to offer an amount of money to support their literary
cause."
</P>
<P>
Under his direct and personal concern, relevant departments,
after a thorough study and research, approved the construction of
a new archives.
</P>
<P>
On November 25, 1996, the foundation of the new archives was
laid in the northern suburbs of Beijing, involving a total
investment of 96 million yuan (about 11.6 million US dollars) and
covering 24,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Shu Yi, son of the late famous writer Lao She and executive
deputy director of the archives, was moved to say: "This is a
great event that the literary circle has long awaited. Almost all
the writers present at the recent writers' congress were inspired
by the good news. It also serves as an practical accomplishment in
socialist cultural and ethical progress."
</P>
<P>
Li Zhun, well-known Chinese writer and Vice-President of the
CWA, said: "From this event, we have come to fully know the
General Secretary's keen concern for China's modern literary cause
and for Chinese writers."
</P>
<P>
"The archives, as a historical monument of modern Chinese
literature, displays the refined literary accomplishments of
modern China," he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhe Taifeng, Deputy Head of the Propaganda Department of the
CPC Central Committee, said the new archives will be a
treasure-house for the safekeeping of the refined literary works
of modern China.
</P>
<P>
"It will continue to play a great role in giving full play to
our national culture, in inspiring our future generations, and in
making further contributions to the world civilization," said Zhe,
who also heads the writers' association.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that all relevant sectors will make every effort to
accomplish this literary project at an early date."
</P>
<P>
This is the wish of Ba Jin. And it also demonstrates the great
concern Jiang Zemin has shown for the country's writers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
