<HEADLINE> Legislators Call for "Absolute Party Leadership" over Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese legislators today
called for stronger leadership by the Chinese Communist Party
(CPC) over the nation's armed forces. Their proposal came during a
discuss in Beijing on a draft law on national defense.
</P>
<P>
"It must be made clear in the law that `absolute party
leadership over the military must be strengthened,' to ensure a
correct political path for the People's Liberation Army (PLA),"
said Huang Yuzhang, Jiang Shunxue, Wang Yuefeng and many other
members of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC) which is now in session.
</P>
<P>
Huang also suggested that an addition be made to the draft
saying that "China will not pose any threat to the security of
other sovereignties" to illustrate China's defense policy of
"active defense."
</P>
<P>
Most lawmakers expressed the view that formulation of the
national defense law is crucial for the rule of law in the
military field.
</P>
<P>
The draft, after several revisions, has emerged as mature and
feasible, according to the committee members. They agreed to
submit the draft after further reviews and revisions to the annual
NPC plenum for deliberation and final approval.
</P>
<P>
Huang Yuzhang proposed a ban on the military from businesses
for profit, and guarantee military expenditure with government
allocations, in order to make the armed forces focus on their
major task of protecting state security.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Shouliang, an NPC deputy from the PLA, and Standing
Committee member Shen Xinsun, said the state should provide
sufficient funds for the development of military technologies,
research and production of new military equipment.
</P>
<P>
Cheng added that more military technicians should be trained to
transfer new hi-tech achievements in the military into combat
power.
</P>
<P>
It should also be written into the law that the PLA should
inherit the glorious traditions of serving the people, austerity
and tight discipline, said Zhou Zhanao, another lawmaker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
