<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Prospects Vary After Elections in Asia, Oceania (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
INDIA -- The United Front (UF) government led by Prime Minister
H.D. Deve Gowda in neighboring India is, likewise, not free from
trouble. For all its seeming stability, the UF, formed in June by
14 smaller disparate parties after the April-May general election,
is still struggling to hold its ground, relying on support from
the Congress Party.
</P>
<P>
The UF coalition became one of the three major political forces
in India after the five-yearly election during which Congress, led
by then prime minister P.V. Narasimha Rao, suffered its worst
defeat at general polls. Rampant corruption, slack organization
and indiscipline, internal strife in Congress' ranks as well as
Rao' arbitrary style were blamed for the party's ouster.
</P>
<P>
The Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), which took
over from Congress as India's largest party with 171 seats in the
545-member parliament, formed a government but resigned after just
two weeks in power, becoming the shortest-lived government in
India's history.
</P>
<P>
The UF and Congress, abhorring the BJP's preached supremacy of
Hinduism and its bias against minority Muslims, joined hands in
bringing down the BJP government.
</P>
<P>
The Congress, which offered vital support to the UF coalition
in order to keep the BJP from power, has since repeatedly
threatened to withdraw its backing. Their "alliance" has been
beset with quarrels, and both Congress and the BJP are biding
their time, eager to regain one-party rule in the future.
</P>
<P>
Deve Gowda last week ruled out snap elections and said his
government would complete its five-year term.
</P>
<P>
However, political analysts predict that a mid-term election is
still likely some time next year.
</P>
<P>
The UF coalition has by and large kept unchanged the previous
government's policies, including economic reform measures,
although its efficiency is marred by parochial views of its
members.
</P>
<P>
Political uncertainty is turning away foreign investments,
slowing down economic growth. However, one thing is clear:
Whoever is in power, the economic reforms launched five years ago
will continue.
</P>
<P>
THAILAND -- The formal swearing in early this month of a
six-party coalition led by Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh
brought to an end a government crisis which had plagued the
previous Banharn Silpa-archa administration.
</P>
<P>
Three cabinet reshuffles amidst an ailing economy caused by
slowing exports growth and sluggish foreign investment failed to
save Banharn's unpopular government which was accused of having
mismanaged the once robust economy and condoning corruption.
</P>
<P>
Banharn was forced by his own coalition allies to agree to
resign during a September debate on an opposition no-confidence
motion which he survived. But instead of actually resigning, he
dissolved the parliament and called fresh elections for November
17.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit's New Aspiration Party (NAP) won the most seats and he
formed the six-party coalition of 221 seats in the 393-member
lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The government of Chavalit, who campaigned on setting up a
"dream team" of technocrats to run key economic ministries, and
his NAP have been hit by internal dissension fueled by
dissatisfaction over the allocation of some key government posts.
</P>
<P>
Political commentators say the Chavalit coalition, an unlikely
"marriage of convenience," may not be able to stay longer than the
previous government -- just over a year.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Chavalit lost no time in announcing major policy
initiatives to tackle national economic woes and the government is
working in earnest to restore confidence in Thailand among local
and foreign investors, eroded by political instability and
economic difficulties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
