<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Prospects Vary After Elections in Asia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUSTRALIA -- In Oceania, Australia's electorate gave Liberal
Party leader John Howard the mandate to form a conservative
coalition government in the March election, ending 13 years of
Labor Party rule under prime ministers Bob Hawke and Paul Keating.
</P>
<P>
Many voters shifted their choice from Keating, whose handling
of the country's economy had been under constant criticism despite
the good score internationally, to Howard just for a change.
</P>
<P>
Howard made adjustments to policies pursued by his predecessor.
The new government's austerity measures appeared to be paying off
with the economy expected to grow by 3.4-four percent this year.
</P>
<P>
But a major row over race and immigration and the new
government's stance towards Asia have aroused great concern both
at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Pauline Hanson, an independent MP, triggered a nationwide
debate on race and immigration in September when she said that
Australia risked being swamped by Asians. Her anti-Asian comments
drew wide criticism and condemnation from Australia's ruling and
opposition parties in parliament, as well as from Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
But Howard repeatedly refused to openly condemn Hanson. Local
press reports said his silence implies support for her views.
</P>
<P>
In its policy towards Asia, what the Howard administration
actually does is starkly different from the Asia-focused Labor
government. The new government attaches priority to Australia's
traditional relationship with America and West Europe, by raising
the level of its military alliance with Washington and preaching
the U.S. military presence in the Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The Howard government's decision to cut soft loan programs to
Asia and its willingness to ape the U.S. in international affairs
contrast sharply with the previous administration's policy of
Australia's "integration into Asia" and the active role it played
in the region.
</P>
<P>
NEW ZEALAND -- New Zealand's first general election on October
12 under a mixed member proportion (MMP) system instead of the
first-past-the-post system ended the traditional domination of
government by either National Party or Labor and heralded a new
era of coalition in New Zealand politics.
</P>
<P>
Although the ruling National and the opposition Labor managed
to retain their positions as the country's two largest political
forces with 44 and 37 seats respectively in the 120-member
parliament, the New Zealand First Party emerged as the biggest
gainer.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen of the newly elected MPs are Maoris. NZ First,
dominated by Maori MPs and led by Maori leader Winston Peters,
fared impressively in the election, benefiting from sharing many
of the conservative National's economic measures and at the same
time the left-leaning Labor's social welfare policy.
</P>
<P>
Peters, whose NZ First held the balance of power after the
inconclusive election, ended two months of political suspense by
choosing National as his coalition partner over Labor, and became
deputy prime minister and gained the powerful post of treasurer.
</P>
<P>
The results of the election did justice to the policies
implemented by the country's political parties since economic
reforms were launched in the early 1980s, and also showed that
more and more New Zealanders tended to favor the centrist line in
politics.
</P>
<P>
The MMP electoral system resulted in a new political pattern in
New Zealand politics which will have a bearing on future policies
of the parties and the government. For all its fairness, the
jitters during the long-drawn-out coalition talks prompted people
to question the wisdom of it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
