<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Announces Price Cuts for IDD Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The price for international
direct dialing (IDD) calls in Macao will be reduced by some 10
percent as of January 1, 1997, the Macao Telecommunications
Company (CTM) announced today.
</P>
<P>
The service charge for mobile phones will also be reduced some
five percent, said CTM.
</P>
<P>
IDD calls to Thailand, the Philippines, Japan, the Republic of
Korea and Portugal will have preferential price treatment during
non-busy hours. The price of IDD calls to Hong Kong will be
reduced from three patacas (about 0.38 US dollars) per minute to
2.6 patacas (about 0.33 US dollars) per minute.
</P>
<P>
Preferential price treatment will also be given to mobile phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CTM said that it will raise the price of rent
for domestic phones. Non-commercial telephone users will have to
pay an extra 10 patacas (about 1.27 US dollars) per month, and
commercial users will have to pay 15 patacas (about 1.9 US
dollars) more each month.
</P>
<P>
The charge for IDD telephone calls has become a hot topic among
local residents over the past several years. The monopoly
operation by the CTM in the past 15 years has brought a fast
modernization of telecommunications in Macao, and many complaints
of high charges as well.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, there had been about one phone for an
average of three residents in Macao, with total lines of telephone
topping 150,000. There are also more than 36,000 mobile phone
users. All phones in Macao can reach 219 countries and regions
around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
