<HEADLINE> Iraq Wants to Improve Ties With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
has said that Iraqi-Turkish relations should be improved as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
He expressed this belief in a message to Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan who met Thursday with visiting Iraqi Oil
Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid in Ankara, according to the local
newspaper Daily News today.
</P>
<P>
No details of the message were made available so far.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said that he supported the removal of the United
Nations sanctions imposed on Baghdad following the 1991 Gulf War
to drive Iraqi troops out of Kuwait, describing the opening of the
Kirkuk-Yumurtalik pipeline as a festive occasion.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamist prime minister complained that the
U.N. sanctions have caused Turkey great economic losses, which
were estimated at 30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"In this way, the embargo on Iraq means an embargo on Turkey,"
Erbakan claimed.
</P>
<P>
Rashid, who is heading a Iraqi government delegation for a
meeting of the Turkish-Iraqi Joint Economic Commission in Ankara,
said that the two countries should exchange views over both
political and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Iraq are planning to launch joint studies on the
development of gas fields in a bid to help Iraq buy badly needed
food and medicine with the sales of gas products.
</P>
<P>
A cooperation protocol is expected to be singed at the end of
the ongoing meeting. 
</P>
