<HEADLINE> Pollution Causes Increase of Respiratory Disease in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Pollution-related
respiratory diseases killed 22,192 people and sent almost half a
million to hospital from 1991 to last year in Hong Kong, and last
year's deaths of the disease were nearly 1,000 more than at the
beginning of the 1990s as air pollutants soared.
</P>
<P>
Today's South China Morning Post reported that over the past
five years pollutants which have been blamed for respiratory
disease rose 14 percent, while other toxic gases increased by 27
percent in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Last year's death toll of 5,707 caused by respiratory disease
was 20 percent higher than the 4,746 deaths recorded in 1991. Eye
doctors and dermatologists said their crowded waiting rooms also
reflected the state of the air, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong authorities warned heart and lung patients to
stay indoors on five occasions this year due to high pollution
levels. Dermatologists say people with eczema may soon receive the
same advice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
