<HEADLINE> Lebanon Issues New Law on News Broadcast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has issued new law on
satellite broadcast to protect the country's international image,
according to Daily Star here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, all news on Katyusha rocket firing by guerrillas
from the Lebanese territory are banned from appearing in satellite
news programs.
</P>
<P>
The Katyusha rocket has been used by Muslim guerrillas in their
fightings against the Israeli occupation forces in south Lebanon,
but a cease-fire understanding reached on April 26 bans any
Katyusha launch into northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Another issue prohibited from being mentioned is the presence
of a 35,000-strong Syrian force in Lebanon, which constitutes the
backbone of Syria's influence in this country, noted the only
English-language daily published in the Lebanese capital.
</P>
<P>
The Information Ministry Thursday outlined the satellite
broadcast law, which also bans news release relating to detentions
of suspects and those wanted by security forces.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Obeid, director general of the ministry, was quoted as
saying that censorship is needed to "protect Lebanon's
international image and refrain from serving Israel's interests
during this crucial post-civil war phase."
</P>
<P>
Obeid said that the regulations were crafted in particular for
Arab audience because other Arab states lack Lebanon's "political
pluralism" and would therefore misinterpret the often turbulent
political scene in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Other news banned by the satellite broadcast law include those
instigating sectarian problems, harming Lebanon's relations with
Arab and foreign countries, and relating to drug cultivation and
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, all news and footages on details of guerrilla
operations against Israel and its backed South Lebanese Army (SLA)
are also banned from being broadcast.
</P>
<P>
The SLA, the militia group trained and armed by the Jewish
state to help police an Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone"
in south Lebanon, was referred to as "the militia collaborating
with Israel" in the new law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
