<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses Canada, US, S.Africa of Derailing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria accused Canada, the
United States and South Africa of planning to derail its
on-going transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in Abuja, capital of Nigeria on Thursday,
Special Duties Minister Alhaji Wada Nas said the three countries,
in conjunction with the Canada-based National Endowment for Democracy
(NED), plan to sponsor "human rights and pro-democracy" groups to
publish leaflits and posters, and organize anti-government rallies,
workshops and press conference in the country.
</P>
<P>
All this is aimed to "undermine the federal government, discredit
the transition program and present it to the internatioanl community
as a manipulative exercise that was devoid of any democratic content,"
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the plan was being hatched following "an unprincipled and
ill-conceived alliance being forged between some foreign diplomats and
the errand boys of Western imperialism namely the so-called
pro-democracy and human rights groups."
</P>
<P>
Only last week, he said, the head of African Affairs of NED visited
Nigeria and met with the leaders of 15 such groups, promising a grant
of 50,000 to 70,000 U.S. dollars to each of them.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the Canadian High Commission in Nigeria provided
about 1.3 million dollars to these groups for the destabilization of
Nigeria, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister named seven of the groups and accused them of
clandestinely receiving money from foreign sources to publish leaflets
that "are nothing but fabrications on the human rights situation in
Nigeria and intended to cause chaos and disaffections among the
populace."
</P>
<P>
He recalled the visit of the United Nations fact-finding mission to
Nigeria in March this year, saying that it has put to rest all the
fabrications about the human rights situation in the country and the
federal government's commitment to the implementation of the
transition program.
</P>
<P>
"The government is faithfully implementing the recommendation of
the UN facting-finding mission," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the recommendation of the mission to the then UN
Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali was in favor of Nigeria and
has been under the attack of Western countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
