<HEADLINE> S.African Black Graduates Suffer Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- South African black
youngsters, who have fortunately finished their courses in
universities, are disappointedly facing a reality -- no ideal
jobs for them.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Central Statistical Service say the total
number of South African graduates is 411,353 with blacks making
up 7.5 percent only.
</P>
<P>
However, of all the poor number of the black graduates, nearly
one fourth of them are unemployed. Such percentage is even far
below that of the unemployed Asian and colored graduates
</P>
<P>
The statistics shows that the unemployment rate among the
Asian and colored graduates registered between three percent and
5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Even the few who are employed constitute less than three
percent of managerial and executive posts", said Vukite Nkabinde,
President of the South African Graduates Development
Assoiciation.
</P>
<P>
Nkabinde complained bitterly about the lack of employment for
black graduates, noting that those doing unchallenging jobs are
paid far less than they are worth.
</P>
<P>
"This might be attributed to the legacy of appartheid,"
Nkabinde said, adding that the effects and consequences of the
large number of unemployed graduates have tended to show in the
crime statistics that have swollen rapidly. 
</P>
