<HEADLINE> Yearender: Prospects Vary After Elections in Asia, Oceania (1) by Ya Tai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- General elections held in
five Asian and Oceanian countries this year all resulted in a
change of government, and in most cases there are signs of
political instability.
</P>
<P>
Political uncertainty has been dogging the governments in
Bangladesh and India ever since they were brought to power by
elections this year, while those who won national polls in
Australia and New Zealand seem to fare better.
</P>
<P>
And Thailand's new cabinet sworn in early this month after over
one year of unstable government may herald the beginning of a
fresh round of instability.
</P>
<P>
BANGLADESH -- The continued antagonism between the government
of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's Awami League (AL) which won
elections in June for the first time in 21 years, and the main
opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) led by Begum Khaleda
Zia does not bode well for the South Asian country of nearly 120
million people, which, plagued by years of chaos, is battling
grinding poverty, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Khaleda, who became the country's first woman prime minister in
1991, won the February 15 election which was boycotted by the then
opposition AL. However, she was forced to step down in late March
amidst a stormy non-cooperation campaign launched by the
opposition, paying the way for fresh polls under neutral caretaker
authority.
</P>
<P>
The AL won the June 12 election which was peaceful and
generally regarded as fair. And riding on people's aspirations
for political stability and economic development, the government
has, among other measures, intensified its economic diplomacy to
attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Disturbances are dwindling and the sagging economy is beginning
to pick up. It is widely believed that if the government focused
its efforts on improving the economy to allow stability to persist
for just one year or two, with subsequent rising popularity for
the AL, the BNP may never be able to stage a comeback.
</P>
<P>
However, instead of seeking to ease the tension with the BNP,
the Hasina government is stepping up "reprisals" against former
BNP government officials in the name of anti-corruption, forcing
the opposition to shift tactics from moderate measures to street
agitation to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
The government's reprisal measures are a double-edged sword and
may become one of the flash points of new violence, and the
country's immediate future remains uncertain, analysts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
