<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Non-Oil/Gas Exports Expected to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Trade and Industry
Minister Tunky Ariwibowo said the country expects a sharp rise in
key non-oil/gas exports in 1997, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The minister told local press Thursday that non-oil/gas exports
are expected to reach 44.7 to 45.1 billion US dollars in 1997, up
from an estimated 38.8 to 39.1 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil/gas imports would be worth 43.8 to 44.2 billion dollars
in the year ahead, up from an expected 39.2 to 39.6 billion this
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's largest exporting industries are electronics,
steel, machinery and automotive, palm oil processing, food and
beverage, and basic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
"The government will encourage the development of these
industries so that their export performance can be maintained," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Government officials have estimated the country's current
account deficit will widen to 8.7 billion US dollars in fiscal
year 1996/97 (April-March), or about 4 percent of gross domestic
product (GDP), from 6.9 billion dollars, or about 3.2 percent of
GDP in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that the country's economic growth was
expected to be between 7.6 and 8.0 percent in 1997 while inflation
was seen at below 7.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government predicted economic growth this year
will be 7.6 to 7.9 percent with inflation rate at 6.5 to 6.8
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
