<HEADLINE> Four Tamil Women Arrested In Eastern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 27 (Xinhua)-- Four Tamil women who carried
over one million rupees (about 18,000 US dollars) strapped to
their bodies were arrested at Kithuhitiyawa in Eastern province
Wednesday, according to police sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that large quantities of medicine were also
detected with them when they were arrested.
</P>
<P>
On interrogation the suspects told the police that they were on
their way to north Jaffna city but were unable to explain how they
got the money, the police said.
</P>
<P>
Police investigations revealed that the suspects had traveled
to Trincomalee by ship and from there were attempting to go to
Jaffna city.
</P>
<P>
Since their explanations were not acceptable, police detained
them for further questioning.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that since the Tamil rebels are hard pressed
for cash and medicine to treat their injured cadres, the women may
be couriers for the Tamil rebels who have been fighting for a
separate state in the north-east of the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
It has been found that Tamil rebel sympathizers in Colombo had
remitted large quantities of money through couriers to Jaffna
city, once their stronghold in the north of the island.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that in this instance the police are yet
unable to find who had given the money to these women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
