<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-Fire Monitors to Meet on Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 27 (Xinhua) -- A five-nation monitoring
committee on Lebanese-Israeli cease-fire is scheduled to meet on
January 6 to assess complaints respectively filed by the two
countries, sources in the Lebanese Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
This will be the eighth meeting since its formation last
August. It comprises France, the United States, Syria, Lebanon and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Michel Gaussot, head of the French delegation in the
committee and the current chairman of the five-nation group,
delivered a copy of Israeli complaint to the Lebanese team
Thursday, the well-informed sources said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Israel filed the complaint Wednesday over a road-side bombing
which killed two Israeli soldiers this week, an Israeli army
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Israel have exchanged accusations against each
other of violating a cease-fire understanding which they reached
on April 26.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire understanding bans Israeli forces and Lebanese
guerrillas from targeting civilian-populated areas or launching
attacks from the areas.
</P>
<P>
Brokered by the U.S., the understanding put an end to a 17-day
Israeli blitz in south Lebanon, which killed some 200 Lebanese,
mainly civilians.
</P>
<P>
Israel charged that the Lebanese pro-Iranian Shiite militia
Hezbollah, or Party of God, spearheading a guerrilla campaign
against the Israeli occupation in south Lebanon, broke the
agreement by detonating a roadside bomb in the village of Markaba
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli soldiers were killed and two others seriously
wounded in the attack. One of the killed was an officer and
member of the elite commando unit "Sayeret Egoxz," according to
the Israeli army spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"This activity by Hezbollah, in an area which is populated by
civilians, is another violation of the understanding," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
But the Lebanese official sources said the Israeli complaint
was "baseless" because the April 26 agreement did not ban
Hezbollah from launching attacks from occupied villages.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Israel filed a complaint over a December 19
Hezbollah operation, claiming that the attack violated the cease-fire
understanding since it was launched from the village of Baraashit
at the north edge of the Israeli-occupied border strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Army General Eli Amitai was sightly injured in the leg
by shrapnel in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon also lodged a complaint over retaliatory Israeli
shelling of the village, in which two civilians were wounded.
</P>
<P>
More than 26 Israeli soldiers have been killed and nearly 90
others wounded so far this year in clashes with Hezbollah
guerrillas in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Israel established the so-called "Security Zone," a
1,100-square-kilometer border strip in south Lebanon, in a bid to
curb cross-border attacks at northern Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
