<HEADLINE> Rescue Operation for Sabah Storm Victims in Full Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Search and rescue
operations for storm victims are in full swing today in East
Malaysia's Sabah which was lashed by a strong rainstorm Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four members of the Special Malaysian Disaster
Assistance and Rescue Team (Smart) today joined in the massive
search and rescue operation launched in Keningau on the state's
west coast, the worst affected by the tropical storm "Greg",
according to reports from Sabah's capital Kota Kinabalu.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be the first time the Smart team, formed
after the Highland Towers collapse tragedy outside Kuala Lumpur in
1994, has moved into action.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Smart members, other rescuers are drawn from the
Police Field Force, border scout and the military.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 Civil Defense Department personnel in Sabah have
already been ordered to take part in relief operations throughout
the state since early Thursday after the rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
Three main relief centers have been set up to house victims.
</P>
<P>
The search and rescue work is currently concentrated in
Keningau, Likas, Tanjung Aru and Kota Kinabalu as well as in the
coastal areas, the reports quoted officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police confirmed 109 bodies had been recovered by
midday today.
</P>
<P>
Among the dead are some foreigners whose identities however
have not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
About 500 houses in nine villages along the Pampang, Bayayo,
Liawan and Sinagang rivers were washed away, leaving about 3,000
people homeless.
</P>
<P>
Road communications from the state capital to Keningau, about
131 kilometers southeast to the state capital, have been severed
after two bridges spanning the Sungai Liawan and Sungai Pegalan
were washed away, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad today extended his
condolences to the families of the victims of the rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
Shocked and sad over the loss of more than 100 lives and the
injuries and damages caused by the tropical storm, Mahathir said
in a statement that the government would help the victims and take
all necessary actions.
</P>
<P>
"The Sabah government and relevant federal agencies have been
directed to provide assistance to the victims of the disaster," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
