<HEADLINE> Malaysia Amends Exchange Control Export Procedures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian National Bank
today announced it has amended the current exchange control
procedures on export of goods effective from January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
These amendments arose from the implementation of the Port
Klang and Subang Airport community systems of the Electronic Data
Interchange (EDI) by the Royal Customs and Excise Department for
processing goods clearance, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendments, an exporter who submits the relevant
Customs/Free Zone declaration forms through the EDI systems would
no longer be required to submit the exchange control form known as
Form KPW X, irrespective of the value.
</P>
<P>
New simplified forms known as Form 5A and Form 5B would be used
instead, with the former for reporting exports with partial or no
payment to be received due to permitted reasons and for changes in
value of export, and the latter for seeking approvals for exports
which do not comply with the normal rules and requirements on
export.
</P>
<P>
For an exporter who does not submit the relevant Customs/Free
Zone declaration forms through the EDI systems, Form KPW X shall
continue to be completed for each export where the value declared
in the relevant export declaration form of Customs/Free Zone
exceeds 100,000 ringgit (about 40,000 US dollars) free on board
(FOB) per shipment.
</P>
<P>
The bank said all other rules and requirements on export, for
exchange control purposes, remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
It said in particular, all payments for export must be received
in Malaysia by the exporter in full and in the prescribed manner
when contractually due, which in any case should not be later than
six months from the date of export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
