<HEADLINE> Israel Annoyed by Italy's Pressure Over Jewish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 27 (Xinhua) -- In an evidence of unsound
relations with the European Union states, Israel has openly
complained to Italy about its support for a U.N. Security Council
plan to dispatch a team to investigate a projected Jewish
settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel has informally, albeit unwillingly, put the Ras al-Amud
settlement issue on hold, asserting that it was not the time for
the Security Council to get involved in the matter, the local
newspaper The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Government officials are quoted as saying that the Italian
government was pushed to get involved in the issue by Palestinian
Authority President Yasser Arafat, who visited Italy lately. Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu is expected to visit Italy and the
Vatican at the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
Officials say Israel is considering raising with the
Palestinians the idea of what they called a "code of conduct,"
whereby the two sides would agree on ground rules of action as
negotiations proceed. As is evidenced by this matter, Israel is
upset that Arafat is lobbying foreign governments to oppose the
Jewish state on specific diplomatic issues.
</P>
<P>
The rightwing Likud-led government has come under mounting
international pressure in recent weeks for its policy of
settlement expansion in the occupied territories. The EU,
enthusiastic in support for the Oslo Accords signed under the
previous Labor government, has been critical of the current
Israeli hardline policy on peace process.
</P>
<P>
The EU has made it clear that it still adheres to the decision
by the U.N. on the status of Jerusalem and therefore disagree
with Israel's assertion that it has exclusive sovereignty over
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
