<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Open Maritime Industry to Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's maritime industry
will be completely opened to foreign investors from January 1999,
the Maritime and Fisheries Ministry announced here today.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will take necessary measures to give foreign
investors full access to sectors such as gas tanker and container
ferry operations, which have been partly or wholly off limits to
foreigners, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It added that foreigners will be able to own a stake in a South
Korean shipping firm or completely take over a South Korean firm
since 1999.
</P>
<P>
Besides, they will be allowed to set up local subsidiaries
instead of agent offices in the country, a move expected to rattle
the entire industry.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot find any more excuses to bar foreign investment in
our maritime industry when South Korean shipping firms make
overseas investments, as was the case of Hanjin Shipping Company
which took over a stake in Germany's DSR-Senator Shipping
Corporation," a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
However, like common practices in other countries, coastal
passenger and cargo transport operations will continue to be
barred from foreign investment, said the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
