<HEADLINE> Chinese Gymnasts Need Consistency and Experience (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Mo Huilan and Bi Wenjing each took one silver, from
vault and uneven bars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Mo, Asian Games champion, lost an opportunity
to win the country the first Olympic women's all-around title as
she stepped out of the carpet following a combination of difficult
moves in her last outing on floor.
</P>
<P>
Mo finished fifth, 0.206 points away from gold medalist Lilia
Podkopayeva of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
To select successors to Li Xiaoshuang and Mo Huilan, China sent
young gymnasts to the world and international competitions.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yufu and Zhao Ji, and Chen Mi and Jin Ying, stole the
limelight at the juniors competitions of the Asian Gymnastics
Championships in China in September, finishing 1-2 in the boys and
girls all-around events respectively.
</P>
<P>
Lu also snatched the all-around title and other three golds at
the Pacific Union gymnastics tournament in Kuala Lumpur last
November.
</P>
<P>
Huang Xu and Zhao Ji also showed good performance at the China
Cup in October and the Pacific Union competitions.
</P>
<P>
Gao Jian, well-known gymnastics coach, said: "I am pleased to
see young gymnasts have made progress, but they have to mature
through international competitions."
</P>
<P>
Gao, who chaired the men's technical committee of the Asian
Gymnastics Union, noted that veterans including Li Xiaoshuang will
retire by the end of 1997 and Chinese women's participants to the
2,000 Olympics will be all new faces.
</P>
<P>
"Thus we should have more high-level coaches to cultivate young
gymnasts," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
