<HEADLINE> Yunnan Province Protects Bioresources with Foreign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kunming, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for the
undertaking of a Sino-Dutch project to protect forests and build
communities in southwest China's Yunnan Province are well under
way.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Jihai, director of the Provincial Forestry
Department, the Dutch government will contribute 15 million US
dollars to the project while the Chinese side, 7.5 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the effort of the province to introduce
overseas funds to protect its rich natural resources and boost
lits economy.
</P>
<P>
Located in southwestern China, Yunnan is known as a "kingdom of
flora and fauna".
</P>
<P>
The province has been utilizing foreign funds to the
bio-diversity and wildlife protection since it began to use funds
from the World Wildlife Fund (WWF) in 1988 to help study the
tropical rain forests in Xishuangbanna.
</P>
<P>
With 12 million Deutsche marks in assistance provided by the
German government to increase the income of farmers in forest
areas, trees have been planted on more than 8,000 hectares and
over 7,400 hectares of forest have been enclosed for natural
growth.
</P>
<P>
This year the Global Environment Fund of the World Bank has
contributed 1.72 million US dollars to a project to manage natural
reserves. The fund will be used for personnel training, scientific
research and improvement of management.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan provincial government is now discussing with the
German government about another project of cooperation in
restoring and protecting tropical rain forests in Xishuangbanna.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the use of foreign funds will focus on protecting the
bioresources and building communities.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the Yunnan provincial government has
allocated nearly 20 million yuan (one RMB yuan equals about 8.3 US
dollars) for the protection of natural reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
