<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Officer: Army Prepared for Syrian Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli army
officer said that the Israeli army has increased its preparedness
for war following Syrian troops' redeployment along Mount Hermon.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post quoted Matan Vilna'i, deputy chief of
Staff of the Israeli army, as saying that the army has
replenished ammunition supplies, introduced advanced artillery,
upgraded tanks and improved exercises.
</P>
<P>
Vilna'i said the military has been preparing for a
confrontation with Syria since August when Syria moved a division
from Beirut, Lebanon's capital, to the slopes of Mount Hermon.
</P>
<P>
Damascus said the troops movement was routine and had no
intention to start a war with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Vilna'i said the army envisions a scenario whereby Syria
attempts a surprise attack on the Golan Heights with a massive
amount of ground troops and tanks.
</P>
<P>
"The likelihood of a war with Syria is greater than it was a
year or two ago," Vilna'i said.
</P>
<P>
The army has determined targets to attack within Syria should
war erupts and increased the level of its standing forces while
providing soldiers with more advanced equipment, he added.
</P>
<P>
The result is that the army has been able to respond to
threats on several fronts simultaneously, he said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy chief of staff stressed that the army has not been
on alert for war, instead, the military is improving its
capability in case of such a development.
</P>
<P>
The standing army has increased 30 percent over the last few
years, Vilna'i said, and the entire corps such as the air force
and intelligence depend solely on recruits.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that the increased number of recruits has been
accompanied by a lack of motivation to serve in combat field
units among Israeli youths.
</P>
<P>
Vilna'i said the benefits of a large standing army were
stressed during the recent tensions with Syria, adding such a
force could manage to repel a massive attack, including the use
of Syrian missiles, until the reserves are mobilized.
</P>
<P>
"A standing army is very expensive," he said. "But, we see the
benefits of large, trained standing army, equipped with the best
weapons. It is the first line of defense."
</P>
<P>
Vilna'i said that during 1997 the Israeli army will receive
several F-151 fighter-jets, Israel's most advanced warplane, Black
Hawk helicopters, Merkava III tanks and MRLS artillery.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that Vilna'i's remarks would add to the tension
between the two countries which were locked in bloody wars in the
past years. No comment was available here from Damascus so far.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors suspended their peace talks early this year
and their relations have deteriorated since the hardline Israeli
government took office in June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0134 </DOCNO>
