<HEADLINE> Chinese Gymnasts Need Consistency and Experience (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua/OANA) -- China's modest collection
at the Atlanta Olympics Games laid bare the fact that their
gymnasts need consistency and experience.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese gymnasts won one gold, four silver and one bronze
medals as against a 2-3-2 finish in the 1992 Olympics in
Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
Spearheaded by Li Xiaoshuang, two-time world champions, China
lost the Olympic men's team title to the Russian squad by a gap of
1.239 points. They picked up the silver medal with 575.539 points.
</P>
<P>
Inconsistency and unsteady nerves cost the Chinese the
most-conveted gold medal as they made too many errors in the last
two of the six rotations to see the Russians pulling away on the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, China found some solace from 1995 world champion
Li Xiaoshuang, who came from behind to score 58.423 points to lift
China's first Olympic all-around title, beating Russian star
Alexie Nemov with a slim margin of 0.049 points.
</P>
<P>
Vitaly Scherbo of Belarus, who swept six golds in the Barcelona
Games, finished third in 58.197. Chinese Zhang Jinjing and Shen
Jian took the fourth and fifth places respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the women's team competitions in Atlanta, 1995 world
championships runners-up China placed a poor fourth as the United
States, Russia and Romania filled the top three spots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
