<HEADLINE> China, CIS Countries Agree on Border Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- After seven years of talks,
China and four members of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) have finally reached a complete agreement here today on the
reduction of military forces in their mutual border regions.
</P>
<P>
The 22th round of talks between China and Russia, Kazakhstan,
Kirghizstan and Tajikistan was held from December 11 to 27.
</P>
<P>
In the past 16 days, a Chinese delegation of foreign and
military experts headed by Ambassador Xia Shuyuan, and a joint
delegation of the four CIS countries led by Ambassador G.V. Kireev
discussed the issue of reducing military forces in their mutual
border areas in a friendly and pragmatic atmosphere, and finally
agreed on the accord of reduction as well as on the contents in
relevent documents.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Zhang Deguang
met with the two delegations. 
</P>
