<HEADLINE> Shenzhen to Pour Huge Investment into Information Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- China's first special
economic zone of Shenzhen, Guangdong Province, will spend 12
billion yuan boosting its information industry during the
1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
As China's only city to try out the information
industrialization, Shenzhen will undertake a host of information
projects during that period.
</P>
<P>
The added value of the city's information industry will amount to
35 billion yuan during that period , increasing at an average
annual rate of 26.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the added value that will come from information
services is expected to top 10 billion yuan, rising 30 percent
annually
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city will expand cooperation with its neighbor
of Hong Kong in such fields as telecommunications, customs
declaration, electronic commercial and trade systems, financial
and statistical information.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen's booming information industry has attracted an
increasing number of transnational information corporations, which
have made huge investments in the city.
</P>
<P>
One of them is the "blue giant" of IBM, which has set up a
purchase center there this year after opening a branch in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has become one of IBM's leading markets and parts
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
The city's information industry turned out information products
valued at 50 billion in 1995. 
