<HEADLINE> India's Central Bank Looses Control on Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) Thursday announced one percent cut in cash reserve ratio
(CRR) in two phases of 0.5 percent each effective from January 4
and January 18, the Times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also advised banks to deploy their funds in
such a manner that the genuine credit needs of all the sectors of
the economy are met.
</P>
<P>
The move will augment lendable resources of banks by 4,275
crore rupees (about 1.22 billion U.S. dollars), a RBI release
said.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to all scheduled commercial banks, RBI said the
decision to give effect to the reduction in CRR from 11 percent to
10 percent has been taken after reviewing the monetary and price
situation which was blamed for the recent slowdown in economic
growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
