<HEADLINE> Large IC Project to Be Launched in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- China has speeded up the
modernization of its electronics industry by announcing a plan to
build a large integrated circuits(IC) production center in
Shenzhen, Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
According to the "People's Posts and Telecommunications News,"
the Zhongxingxin Telecom Equipment LTD., a Shenzhen-based telecom
supplier, and a local hi-tech company have signed an agreement to
form an investment consortium. The project will involve the
introduction of funds from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Involving 1.4 billion US dollars in investment, the project
aims to establish a producing base for the super-IC chips, which
will be 0.25 to 0.35 microns thick and eight inchs wide. When
completed, the project will have a minimum monthly production
capacity of 20,000 units.
</P>
<P>
In addition to boosting China's fledgling IC production, local
industrial analysts said, the project will help the country raise
the ratio of domestically-produced parts in telephone switching
systems and other electronics products, paving the way for a
take-off in the national information industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
