<HEADLINE> Protest, But No March in Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Serbian opposition
supporters held a protest rally in central Belgrade Thursday
without walking on the streets as they have done over the past 36
days.
</P>
<P>
The protesters' move, apparently aimed at avoiding direct
confrontation with riot police, came after the Interior Ministry
issued a ban on Wednesday on marches which disrupted traffic.
</P>
<P>
They assembled in front of the headquarters of the Democratic
Party and listened to the President of the Serbian Renewal
Movement, Vuk Draskovic, who suggested a shorter "stroll" because
of the bad weather.
</P>
<P>
The protesters all went home after the rally instead of
marching in the streets to protest against the government's
annulment of the results of local elections on November 17.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations by Serbian citizens and students against the
government started two days after the November 17 elections. On
Tuesday, government supporters and pro-opposition demonstrators
clashed in the streets, causing dozens of injuries. 
</P>
