<HEADLINE> U.S. to Install Bomb-Detection Equipment at Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA) today announced a 52.2 million dollar
contract to install sophisticated X-ray equipment at major
airports in the United States to detect explosives in checked
baggage.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract with InVision Technologies of Foster City,
California, the installation of the equipment will start next
month and a total of 53 such machines will be put at U.S. airports
in 1997. But for security reason, the FAA would not disclose the
names of the airports that will have the equipment.
</P>
<P>
The contract is part of the government's efforts in tightening
security at airports after the explosion of TWA Flight 800 last
summer although investigators have yet to determine if the TWA
crash was a terrorist attack or mechanical malfunction.
</P>
<P>
The FAA also said that it was to hire 300 more special agents,
upgrade security requirements and improve background checks on
airport employees.
</P>
<P>
The government has the option to purchase additional systems in
1998. The system, called the CTX-5000, is the only detection
system to have passed the FAA's certification test. 
</P>
</TEXT>
