<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Says Private Sector Alone Cannot Provide Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The private sector alone cannot
deliver efficient public services, according to the latest issue
of the ADB Review, the bi-monthly publication of the Asian
Development Bank (ADB).
</P>
<P>
Public and private sectors must work together to inject greater
competition, increase efficiency and avert market failures.
Privatization program must be carefully designed and regulated in
light of many drawbacks experienced in privatization and private
provision of service, the Review said.
</P>
<P>
In some cases, privatized public institutions were put to some
other use or entered into monopolistic contracts for service
delivery, increasing fees while allowing services to deteriorate,
the Review said, pointing out the government intervention is thus
needed.
</P>
<P>
In a related article, an ADB-financed study of the social
sector in Asian transition economies showed the division of
responsibilities between the public and private sectors in social
service delivery is difficult but even more complex in transition
economies.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rapid growth in private sector activities in these
economies, the public sector still has a major role in ensuring
equity of access to these services.
</P>
<P>
Regulating the newly emerging private sector, ensuring fair
competition between public and private operations, and divesting
state enterprises of services that are better provided by the
private sector are issues that will have to be addressed in each
country, the Review concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
