<HEADLINE> Ramos Acts to Break Budget Deadlock Between Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos is looking for a compromise on the 1997 national budget,
whose passage was blocked due to a deadlock between the House of
Representatives and the Senate, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ramos made this indication after undergoing a successful
operation to remove a cholesterol block in his carotid artery. He
checked out of hospital and returned to work on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"President Ramos will talk to leaders of both chambers of
Congress to determine what is the problem and how we can help
solve the problem," Executive Secretary Ruben Torres said.
</P>
<P>
On the first day he returned to the Presidential Palace, Ramos
met with Senate President Ernesto Maceda who said later that Ramos
seemed to like the Senate's formula on how to solve the budget
dispute.
</P>
<P>
The two chambers are giving two repaired versions of the 1997
draft budget and disagreed with each other. The core of the
standoff was the Senate's proposed 40-percent cut in the
Countrywide Development Fund (CDF) of all legislators.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with the President, Maceda proposed to
reduce the CDF allocations by 20 percent instead of the 40 percent
cut the senate earlier stuck to.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that Congress adjourned for the month-long
Christmas break without passing the 476.2-billion-peso (18.2
billion U.S. dollars) budget proposed for next year.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is supposed to meet today to discuss how to solve
the country's budget crisis. 
