<HEADLINE> Southern Jiangsu Improving Waterways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The realignment of the south
Jiangsu section of the Grand Canal is near completion after four
years' construction.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, more than 90 percent of the earthwork
had been finished. Thirty bridges had been built, 71 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
An accumulated investment of 1.18 billion yuan had been spent,
78.6 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The 1,794-km Grand Canal, linking Beijing with Hangzhou in east
China's Zhejiang Province and built in the Sui Dynasty (581-618),
runs 700 km through Jiangsu.
</P>
<P>
The transport volume of the canal accounts for over 50 percent
of the total water transports for the province.
</P>
<P>
The northern Jiangsu section of the canal was realigned before
1989.
</P>
<P>
The 208-km southern Jiangsu section, running through
economically-developed Suzhou, Wuxi, Changzhou and Zhenjiang, is
one of the businest waterways of the country. The year 1989 saw
its transport volume surpass 100 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The realignment of the southern Jiangsu section began in August
1992. The estimated total input amounts to 1.502 billion
yuan. The project is scheduled to be completed at the end of
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
