<HEADLINE> Snowstorm Whips Up Romania, Bulgaria Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Heavy snow and blizzards
swept large areas of Romania and Bulgaria Wednesday and Thursday,
suspending road and water traffic and closing airports -- but the
weather brought an unexpected meeting between the two countries'
presidents.
</P>
<P>
The bad weather forced the aircraft of Bulgarian President
Petar Sroyanov, who was returning from a trip to Italy, to land in
Bucharest Thursday.
</P>
<P>
His aircraft had been heading for Sofia. But the heavy snow
that suspended road traffic in northern and eastern Bulgaria
closed Sofia airport and two others, forcing the aircraft to
divert to Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
The Black Sea ports of Varna and Burgas also closed because of
high waves caused by strong winds. Electricity was cut in nearly
400 villages across Bulgaria, and in some areas water supplies
were suspended.
</P>
<P>
The heavy snow was expected to last for another two days in
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
Air transport in neighboring Romania was able to operate as
usual, except for one airport which cancelled flights because of
thick fog.
</P>
<P>
But snowstorms brought down wires, and delayed trains and
suspended road transport in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Strong winds brought blizzards and whipped up six-meter waves
along the Black Sea coast, forcing the port of Constanca to close
and paralyzing service on the Danube River.
</P>
<P>
The first snow of the winter in Romania came a month later than
usual and brought a snow blanket averaging 20-30 centimeters thick
to many areas. In some places, the snow was up to 70-80
centimeters deep.
</P>
<P>
In Bucharest, Sroyanov was invited by Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu to the presidential place, where the two discussed
issues of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Though not scheduled in advance, both sides believed the
meeting would help promote mutual understanding, said a spokesman
of Constantinescu's press office.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Sofia said Sroyanov left for Bulgaria by road on
Thursday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
