<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Oil Production Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' oil fields
produced a measly 270,000 barrels of crude oil this year, a 75
percent decline from 1.067 million barrels last year, according
to the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
The department, in its year-end report, attributed the sharp
decline to the suspended oil production at the Linapacan oil
field, one of the country's major oil producers.
</P>
<P>
The Linapacan wells, which stopped production this January,
registered an output of a mere 5,312 barrels, a 99 percent drop
compared to 703,011 barrels last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's oil production went 45 percent below
the target of 600,000 barrels for 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the domestic oil production had been slow
also partly due to a drop in output in another oil field, Nido, in
the southern Philippines. Production at the Nido wells dropped by
14 percent to 174,821 barrels from 203,707 barrels a year ago.
</P>
<P>
But the report said the Matinloc field in the southern
Philippines produced a total of 94,1986 barrels of crude oil this
year, more than double the production of 45,908 barrels last year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
