<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' GNP Growth to Outpace Inflation in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines expects the national economy to grow faster than the
inflation rate next year, with gross national product (GNP)
expanding between seven and eight percent against an inflation
rate of six to seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank governor Cabriel Singson said in a report to
President Fidel Ramos that economic growth has actually outpaced
inflation since the third quarter this year, the Philippine Star
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Average inflation, Singson said, slowed down to 6.1 percent in
the second half of the year, compared with 11.1 percent in the
first half, while the economy grew by 7.1 percent in the first
three quarters.
</P>
<P>
"The strong economic results achieved in 1996 have by now
clearly established the ability of the economy to stay on a high
growth path without necessarily running into financial imbalance,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Singson attributed the achievement of high growth and low
inflation to the improvement in the government's finances, the
series of policy reforms, improved administrative capacity and
political stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines last experienced a higher growth, lower
inflation scenario in 1987 at a much lower level with a GNP growth
of 4.6 percent and an inflation rate of three percent. 
</P>
