<HEADLINE> Winter in Beijing Fails to Deter Keen Exercisers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Cold and windy winter has
failed to frozen the enthusiasm of morning exercisers in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Every morning Beijingers, most of them middle-aged or elderly,
rally in parks, stadiums and open spaces. People walk, jog or
stretch, play badminton or foot-shuttlecock, or practise
traditional Yangko dancing, kungfu or qigong.
</P>
<P>
Yuyuantan Park, in western Beijing, attracts thousands of
fitness enthusiasts each day around the edge of its large
lake. Some arrive as early as 4 am, nearly two hours before dawn
in mid-winter.
</P>
<P>
Despite thick ice covering most parts of a big lake in the
park, swimmers plunge into the icy water to the amazement of
spectators in bulky winter clothes.
</P>
<P>
Other large Beijing parks also have 1,000 to 1,500 exercisers
each morning, said a report in today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guanmin, 69, chooses an unique way to keep fit. While
practising a traditional breathing exercise, he whoops every four
or five steps.
</P>
<P>
"Yelling can let out both mental stress and internal physical
waste accumulating overnight," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, the city has launched a campaign to encourage
all city residents to join in physical exercises.
</P>
<P>
Stadiums, track fields and fitness centers open to the public
day and night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
