<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Welcomed to Upgrade Battery Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- China's battery makers should
shift their focus to alkaline battery production to avoid losing
their potential market shares, According to "China Daily" today.
</P>
<P>
With an annual output of more than 10 billion batteries, China
is the world's largest battery producer, accounting for one-third
of the total.
</P>
<P>
The country expects to export more than half of batteries this
year, earning 300 million yuan, nearly the same as in 1995, said
Wang Jingzhong, secretary-general of the China Battery Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
Domestic makers often find it hard to place their products in
the supermarkets in China's big cities. The supermarkets stock
foreign-brand alkaline batteries, including Duracell, Energizer,
Toshiba and National.
</P>
<P>
China expects to produce around 300 million alkaline batteries,
a small proportion of the country's total battery output, Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
About 200 million alkaline batteries are for the domestic
market, leaving the remainder of the market demand to be met by
imports.
</P>
<P>
As people become more conscious of environmental protection,
low-capacity and low-power batteries will sooner or later give way
to pollution-free alkaline ones, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Many domestically made alkaline batteries made in east China's
Fujian Province are as high-quality as imported ones. Nanfu
alkaline batteries enjoy a good market for their high quality and
low price, with about 70 percent exported to the United States,
Japan and European countries.
</P>
<P>
But current alkaline battery production is too small-scale in
China. And the country welcomes foreign investment to upgrade
battery quality and to expand alkaline battery production, Wang
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
