<HEADLINE> Peruvian Rebels Free Guatemalan Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian rebels occupying the
Japanese embassy residence here released Guatemalan ambassador
Jose Maria Argueta today in a gesture to recognize his country's
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The release left 103 people still held captive by members of
the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA), who have been
occupying the residence since December 17. Around 30 of the
remaining hostages are Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The Guatemalan government and the rebel National Revolutionary
Unity are expected to sign a peace treaty on Sunday, putting an
end to the 36-year-old civil war, reports said.
</P>
<P>
After the release of Argueta, President Alberto Fujimori met
with Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, who arrived
here Thursday to learn of government effort to free hostages,
including Malaysian ambassador Ahmad Mokthar Selat.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a loud explosion occurred in the besieged residence,
causing fears for the safety of the remaining hostages.
</P>
<P>
A bishop who entered the compound told reporters that the
captives were not hurt in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Red Cross officials said an animal stepping on a mine near the
building might have been responsible for the mysterious blast.
</P>
<P>
The blast could have come from a homemade mine of the type the
rebels have allegedly placed around the building, police said.
</P>
<P>
After releasing hundreds of hostages, the rebels continue to
hold 103 captives they consider most useful as bargaining chips,
including Peruvian ministers, diplomats and Japanese businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori has flatly rejected the rebels' demands that more than
400 of their jailed comrades be freed, telling them to hand over
their weapons and release their captives if they want to avoid the
use of force.
</P>
<P>
The crisis began on December 17 when the rebels stormed the
residence during a gala reception honoring the Japanese emperor's
birthday.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan ambassador Tabare Bocalandro was freed Tuesday, after
a Uruguayan court ordered the release of two suspected MRTA
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
