<HEADLINE> Philippine Government, Muslim Rebels to Open Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have agreed to open
their overdue peace talks on January 7, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which will be held in Sultan Kudarat province as
agreed earlier, will be at technical levels only, the reports
quoted Executive Secretary Ruben Torres as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The technical committees from both parties will discuss only
the details and parameters of their formal peace negotiations,
Torres said.
</P>
<P>
Torres said the MILF agreed to the date so as not to interrupt
the Ramadan, the Muslim's month-long fasting ritual which will
begin on January 9.
</P>
<P>
Torres said he is optimistic the MILF will honor the agreed
date. He did not explain why the MILF gave up the January 3 date
they proposed earlier.
</P>
<P>
The exploratory peace talks between the government and the MILF
have been delayed since early October because of tit-for-tat
attacks between the two sides, and disagreement over a temporary
truce and the venue of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF), is one of the several rebel groups still
fighting the government.
</P>
<P>
The MILF refused to honor the peace deal forged in September
between the government and the MNLF, and wants its own peace
negotiations with the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
