<HEADLINE> Price War to Heat Microwave Ovens in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The microwave-oven price war
in major Chinese cities is likely to be more intense next year, as
the market expands and domestic producers grow stronger.
</P>
<P>
The price war is likely be as fierce as that in the
refrigerator market four years ago and more recent price wars in
the air-conditioner and color TV markets, China Daily quoted Pan
Weiji, deputy domestic sales manager for Galanz, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Microwave ovens have begun to enter ordinary Chinese urban
households in large numbers in recent years, prompting the
emergence of a huge market.
</P>
<P>
Prior to 1994, imported microwave ovens, especially Japanese
ones, dominated the domestic market. But development of microwave
ovens by Chinese manufactures led to a 50-50 split last year
between domestic and foreign producers.
</P>
<P>
The price war on microwave oven began in August this year when
Guangdong Galanz Group, the largest domestic producer of microwave
ovens, cut the prices of its two most popular models by nearly 40
percent. Most domestic producers, including foreign-invested ones,
followed Galanz's lead.
</P>
<P>
Some domestic producers have won customers with low prices,
better services and good after-sales services such as one-year to
three-year guarantees or lifetime repairs. Other producers
launched campaigns to promote the making of traditional Chinese
dishes using microwave ovens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
