<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds, Technology Boost China's Telecom Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- China's telecommunications
industry has used 6.56 billion US dollars in foreign loans over
the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
The loans, accounting for one fifth of the fixed assests of the
whole industry, were used to import advanced telecom products and
technologies, and beef up the domestic telecom systems, according
to the Beijing-based "People's Posts and Telecommunications News."
</P>
<P>
China's first telecom import item was a 10,000-line switching
system which was installed in Fuzhou, capital of east China's
Fujian Province, in 1982.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last November, China had increased its phone
switching capacity to 100 million lines, 16 times that of 1982,
and signed up more than 6.5 million mobile phone users.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the import of sophisticated foreign technologies in
the past decade, China now has 11 telephone switch makers with a
combined annual production capacity of 25 million lines.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 million lines of program-controlled switchboards
manufactured by these plants have been installed on China's public
telecom networks, accounting for 53 per cent of the country's
total.
</P>
<P>
China is now capable of developing the high-speed SDH
(synchronous digital hierarchy) transmission system which has a
speed of 2.5 Gb/s, intelligent network and ISDN (integrated
service digital network) system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
