<HEADLINE> Panama Congress to Legislate on Canal Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian Legislative
Assembly is discussing a bill which will regulate the appointment
of executives and the functions of the new Panama Canal Board of
Directors.
</P>
<P>
The bill was presented to the Legislative Assembly by Foreign
Minister Ricardo Arias.
</P>
<P>
Arias said the Board of Directors would have 11 members, and
the president and nine officials would be appointed by the
government, and another by the plenary session of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
The law rules, among other measures, that the highest authority
in the Panama canal will have autonomy and minister's rank.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister stressed that with this law, Panama was
preparing the juridical framework to administer the important
interoceanic waterway which will revert to Panama on the last day
of 1999 from the United States, its present administrator.
</P>
<P>
The bill also stipulates that the new Canal authority will
function as a regime of planning and financial administration for
three-year periods.
</P>
<P>
When the all-Panamanian administrative board assumes direction
of the Canal installations, the Canal budget will be autonomous
and not part of the state general budget.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Assembly will only be able to approve or reject
it, but not modify it in any way.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of toll fees, the bill said they would be
determined to cover the costs of the operation and modernization
of the waterway, as well as payments due to the national treasury.
</P>
<P>
Some Canal users have expressed concern about toll raises
announced for next year by the present Canal Board of Directors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Adopts Regulation to Control Ground Subsidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has adopted a
regulation to help control the city's sinking feeling.
</P>
<P>
China's largest city is sinking slowly at the rate of ten
millimeters a year, caused by excessive extraction of groundwater
and the sheer weight of its buildings, said Zhang Xianlin,
director of the Shanghai Geological Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
 The new rule is aimed at controlling ground subsidence,
according to a report.
</P>
<P>
The regulation, with a total of 18 clauses, will help protect
ground subsidence monitoring facilities and promote the research
into geological hazards, ``China Geology and Mineral Resources"
reported.
</P>
<P>
With a population of some 13 million, the municipality's
consumption of drinking water and that used in industry has been
on the rise over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has taken preventative steps to halt
subsidence, such as controlling the amount of groundwater taken
from the shallow layer, replenishing groundwater, and drawing
water from a deep stratum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
