<HEADLINE> Business News in Brief in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are business news
in brief in the Philippines today:
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Bank of the Philippines is lifting the ceiling
on domestic borrowings of foreign companies starting January.
According to an original rule enacted in 1977, foreign firms in
the country were required to maintain a debt-to-equity ratio of
7:3 or 6:4, depending on their industry category. This determined
the amount of loanable funds these firms can source from local
bank and nonbanks. With this rule repealed, foreign firms will now
be able to compete on equal footing with their local counterparts
for resources in the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Bank of the Philippines said in its year-end
report that heavy private capital inflows and increased
remittances from overseas Filipino workers are expected to boost
the country's balance of payment surplus to four billion U.S.
dollars this year, up by more than 500 percent from 631 million
U.S. dollars last year. However, the bank said the country's
current account deficit is to widen this year to an equivalent of
4.2 percent of the gross national product (GNP) from 2.6 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
-- Investments registered with the country's economic zones for
the year have soared to 65.3 billion pesos (2.5 billion U.S.
dollars), up by 24.3 percent from last year. However, the
Philippine Economic Zone Authority said the figure is still 14
percent below its 75 billion peso (2.86 billion U.S. dollar)
projection for the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
