<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Becomes China's Second Largest Energy Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region, north China, has turned itself into the country's second
largest energy base, "Economic Information News" reported.
</P>
<P>
The region, the country's second largest coal producer after
Shanxi Province, is capable of producing 64 million tons of raw
coal a year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it is able to produce 1.76 million tons of crude oil
and generate more than 28 billion kilowatt hours of electricity
annually.
</P>
<P>
One third of the electricity produced by the region is sent to
northeast China, Beijing, Tianjin and Tangshan cities, and even to
the country of Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Significantly, one fourth of Beijing's power supplies comes
from the region.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia has given priority to the development of energy
industry by giving preferential treatment in funding and
policies. Over the past five years, the region's output value
from the energy industry grew at an annual rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
At present, China's biggest open-cut coal mine, Asia's largest
thermal power station, and several oilfields are under
construction in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
