<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks Ways to Reduce After-Quake Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The State Seismological Bureau
held a three-day conference in Shanghai on anti-earthquake
emergency measures in large Chinese cities, according to China
Daily today.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 government officials and seismologists gathered
to discuss ways to reduce damages after a possible earthquake hits
a big city during the conference, which closed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China Daily noted that the conference is the first of the kind
held since the founding of new China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
The conference participants have shared their experiences in
quake disaster reduction. They praised Baotou, a big industrial
city in Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, for its post-quake
recovery.
</P>
<P>
On May 3, a quake measuring 6.4 on the Richter scale jolted
areas west of Baotou, killing 26 people, injuring some 400
people and leaving 500,000 people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The Inner Mongolia and Baotou governments have made great
efforts to reconstruct the damaged city and all 500,000 people
have left the makeshift shelters to move into houses equipped with
heating systems.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been paying close attention to the
emergency anti-quake work. The State Council has worked out a
10-year plan on earthquake disaster reduction, under which all
Chinese large and medium-sized cities should suffer reasonably
small property damages and casualties after a quake with a
Richter scale magnitude of 6 or more.
</P>
<P>
So far, 20 central government ministries and commissions, 23
provinces and 15 provincial capital cities have mapped out
emergency plans to deal with any possible earthquake.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
