<DOCNO> XIE19961227.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution Control Makes Progress in Songhua River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin and
Heilongjiang provinces have improved pollution control in the
Songhua river, one of the country's seven major rivers, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that the Jilin Chemical Industrial Group and the
Jilin Paper Mill have spent more than 100 million yuan in
building and expanding sewage treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
Harbin, capital of Heilongjiang province, has completed a major
waste-water treatment project.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, the 1,840-kilometer-long Songhua River has
been contaminated by industrial waste water and untreated
household sewage.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1950s and early 1960s, the Songhua was seriously
polluted by mercury and people's health was harmed by mercury
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
After decades of pollution treatment and preventive measures,
the sources of mercury pollution were effectively controlled.
</P>
<P>
Although mercury pollution was under control, other pollution
sources, like coal-fired power stations, textile-dyeing mills and
paper mills, remained a threat.
</P>
<P>
Cities in the Songhua valley also discharge large quantities of
untreated household sewage into the river.
</P>
<P>
Toxic substances in the untreated waste water have damaged the
river's aquatic resources.
</P>
<P>
In the mid-1950s the river teemed with fish, but today few fish
remain.
</P>
<P>
Water pollution is also endangering drinking-water supplies for
many cities, including Harbin.
</P>
<P>
Four major construction projects by Songhua Lake, in the river
valley and near Jilin, have occupied or plan to occupy a total of
6.15 hectares of forest.
</P>
<P>
Due to the destruction of forests for construction projects,
soil erosion has left 822.32 square kilometers of land barren,
16.2 percent of the total landspace in the lake area.
</P>
<P>
Jilin province has implemented regulations to enforce stricter
controls on construction projects around the lake, and initial
success has been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
