<HEADLINE> Riots Hit Tasikmalaya, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jakarta, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people in
Tasikmalaya, West Java, Indonesia, have been on a rampage through
the town since Thursday morning and in the process damaged or
destroyed a number of cars, shops, churches and local
administration buildings.
</P>
<P>
The street actions were still going on Thursday afternoon with
the material toll reported to be at least five churches and two
cars damaged, official Antara news agency reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported the rioters had set fire to shops and
elementary school buildings and damaged the local police
headquarters and legislative council.
</P>
<P>
But until Thursday afternoon there was no report of human
casualties.
</P>
<P>
Dudung Abdul Halim, chairman of the Tasikmalaya chapter of the
Council of Indonesian Ulemas (MUI), meanwhile expressed his deep
regret as the riot was apparently related to an incident last
December 23 in which a few local police officers had maltreated
three Islamic preachers.
</P>
<P>
From Ciamis, capital of another district in West Java, it was
reported security personnel Thursday blocked the road connecting
Ciamis with Cijolang village to its east to prevent hundreds of
people from entering the town. Cijolang village is located on the
border between West Java and Central Java.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreak of the riot, shops in Tasikmalaya and Ciamis
have been closed.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said the mass violence was triggered by an
incident that occurred on December 23 involving four local
policemen, three Islamic preachers and students of the Condong
Islamic Boarding School in the Cibeureum sub-district.
</P>
<P>
The policemen had allegedly beaten up the three Islamic
preachers for having physically punished a student at the Condong
Boarding School accused of pilfering school property. The erring
student happened to be the son of a local police officer.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic boarding school teachers reportedly struck the
student's legs with a palm leaf rib and subsequently threw him
into a pond. The student was said to have stolen school property
at least three times.
</P>
<P>
on December 24, chief of the Tasikmalaya district police Lt.
Col. Suherman offered apologies to the Islamic preachers and
visited a number of other boarding schools to explain what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
Suherman also ordered the arrest of the four high-handed
policemen and a spokesman for the West Java provincial police
command, while Lt. Col. Istanto Judihardjo gave the assurance that
the guilty police officers would be duly disciplined.
</P>
<P>
Suherman's efforts and Judihardjo's assurance, however, proved
unable to prevent the happenings from eliciting the negative mass
reactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
