<HEADLINE> French Olympic Champ Calls for Policing of Skiing Slopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 26 (Xinhua) -- French Olympic champion Marielle
Goitschel called on Thursday for ski slopes to be policed and
skiers punished for speeding after two holidaymakers died in
skiing collisions in French Alpine resorts last week, according to
the local TV reports.
</P>
<P>
"Ski runs have turned into the Wild West. We need a law,"
Goitschel, gold medalist in the 1964 and 1968 winter Olympics,
told TF1 television.
</P>
<P>
"We must protect the 95 percent of normal people from the five
percent of crazies," she said.
</P>
<P>
Goitschel, who now runs the Val Thorens resort, has written to
President Jacques Chirac proposing that ski instructors act as
"police", watching out for hazardous skiing and seizing ski passes
from offenders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
