<HEADLINE> OSCE Should Neither Arbitrate Nor Mediate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Senior Yugoslav officials
said today that the recent visit of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to Belgrade was neither to
arbitrate nor to mediate in current political events in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The visit of an OSCE delegation last weekend "is a
confirmation of Yugoslavia's efforts to establish good relations
with the international community," Deputy Prime Minister Nikola
Sainovic and Deputy Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic of
Yugoslavia told foreign reporters at a joint press conference in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Sainovic said Felipe Gonzales, head of the OSCE delegation and
the organization's representatives, had come to Yugoslavia not to
mediate nor to arbitrate the political developments in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The opposition coalition Zajedno has been staging rallies and
demonstrations since November 19 to protest the annulment of
results of the local election in which it claimed victory in most
major cities in Serbia. The daily protests in Belgrade and
throughout Serbia have caused a political crisis in Yugoslavia and
aroused concerns from the international community.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, the Serbian government had invited an
OSCE team to visit Belgrade last weekend to find out the truth of
the election dispute between the government and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Sainovic said many foreign representatives who had come to
Yugoslavia often changed their views under pressure from different
centers of power, despite what they had seen in the field.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Gonzales would reach conclusions in
accordance with what he had seen and what he had said during talks
in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister Jovanovic added that the idea to invite
the OSCE delegation was to contribute to normalization of relations
between Yugoslavia and the international community and speed up an
already advanced process of normalization of Yugoslavia's
relations with the OSCE.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the visit will be conducive to that aim," said
Jovanovic, who also expressed the hope that the OSCE report would
reflect that principled stand.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE delegation is expected to submit a fact-finding report
to the Vienna-based organization Friday.
</P>
<P>
"However, should the case be otherwise, Yugoslavia will retain
its principled stands, because the issues concerned are the
internal questions of a sovereign state to be settled solely
within the institution of the political system, i.e., without
outside mediation or arbitration," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to deal with our problems within the valid
constitutional order, because only these institutions provide for
democratic solutions," Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
He said that all ambitions and wishes directed at seeking
solutions outside the institutions of the political system,
regardless of whether coming from within the country or outside,
were simply not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Serbian government supporters and opposition
coalition followers fought against each other with sticks and
flagpoles, causing injuries to dozens of people and further
strained relations between the government and the opposition.
Zajedno leaders have said they would not open dialogue with the
government until the annulled election results had been
reinstated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
