<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Minister: Citizens Fed up with Daily Rallies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Interior Minister
Vukasin Jokanovic said today that Belgrade citizens are fed up
with daily rallies and protests because they cannot go where they
want or use city traffic or even their own cars.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Serbian Interior Ministry statement that
police will no longer allow the arbitrary blocking of traffic,
Jokanovic said at a federal assembly session, "There are many
places where peaceful demonstrations can be held, and sidewalks
are for walks."
</P>
<P>
The Serbian Interior Ministry said Wednesday night that the
police will not allow the arbitrary blocking of traffic and
demonstration organizers are obliged to use their right to
peaceful demonstrations only in keeping with the laws.
</P>
<P>
It also underscored that police will intervene in agreement
with regulations and their duty in implementing the law and
protecting the rights of citizens in the event of breaches of the
law and further violations of public law and order.
</P>
<P>
The new measure was taken after incidents occurred Tuesday when
government supporters and opposition coalition followers clashed
in central Belgrade, causing injuries to dozens of people from
both sides.
</P>
<P>
The opposition coalition Zajedno has organized demonstrations
and rallies over the past 37 days to protest the alleged election
fraud by the government, blocking street traffic in Belgrade and
affecting local people's normal life.
</P>
<P>
When asked why the police did not come into the streets of
Belgrade earlier Tuesday, but only after incidents began,
Jokanovic said the police came out "the moment they deemed it
necessary, and they counted on the citizens having opted for
peaceful manifestations and rallies."
</P>
<P>
Jokanovic also stressed that police would never use force
against citizens who protest peacefully.
</P>
<P>
No one, not even the Belgrade police chief who is in charge of
regulating city traffic, would undertake anything outside the law,
he added.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, hundreds of riot police were deployed in the
streets to maintain smooth traffic and guard against possible
further clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
