<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Projects in Five Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of financing for five projects in five
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's Global Environment Facility offered a grant of
32.8 million U.S. dollars equivalent for China's industrial
boilers project. The project will introduce combustion systems and
equipment needed to help China upgrade heating and power boilers,
introducing modern manufacturing techniques and new boiler
designs.
</P>
<P>
The International Development Association (IDA), the
concessionary lending arm of the World Bank, okayed a credit of
34.7 million dollars for India's environment management capacity
building project. The project will provide technical assistance
and training to the Indian government to strengthen its
environmental policy planning, administration and its
implementation of legislation.
</P>
<P>
Another IDA credit of 55 million dollars equivalent will be
used for Vietnam's rural transportation project. The resources
will finance the purchase of vehicles, equipment and materials to
maintain and improve roads and bridges in 15 provinces.
</P>
<P>
An IDA credit of 30 million dollars is earmarked for Yemen's
emergency flood rehabilitation project. The credit will finance
rebuilding of embankments and other flood protection works such as
irrigation systems, canals, wells and service roads.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank also approved a 7 million dollar loan to assist
Kazakstan finance the purchase of goods and materials needed to
rebuild the Aralsk-Sarbulak pipeline and support related
consultant services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
