<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt no longer needs credit from international
financial establishments thanks to the rich influx of foreign
investments and improved economic situation in the country
following 15 years of economic reforms, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian Weekly Al Ahram which was
published today, Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Youssef
Boutros-Ghali said that foreign investment this year amounted to 3
billion U.S. dollars, six times of the projected figure. In 1997,
it will reach 5 billion dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the International Monetary Fund has recognized Egypt as
a good performer in the world economic community.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, Egypt no longer needs loans from outside
financial institutions especially when the economic growth rate
has reached a level making the soft loans unnecessary, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign currency reserve has risen to 19 billion
dollars, with stability facilitated in the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Iraq will buy at least 21 million U.S. dollars worth
of Egyptian vegetable oil and soap in one of its first purchases
of food and other daily necessities since resuming oil exports
recently.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) today reported that
the Egyptian Holding Company for Food Industries has just
concluded a deal on providing Iraq with the edible oil.
</P>
<P>
The 8 million U.S. dollar deal, which is to be signed next
week, will bring the total sum of agreements between Egypt and
Iraq up to 21 million dollars, the MENA quoted a business source
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The company signed two days ago a 13-million-dollar deal to
export vegetable oil and soap to Iraq under the United Nations
oil-for-food agreement.
</P>
<P>
So far, 29 countries and regions have offered to sell food and
medicine to Baghdad, following the six years of international
embargo since the 1990-1991 Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Cairo -- Egypt and Saudi Arabia signed agreements on
investments worth more than one billion U.S. dollars during a
visit by an Egyptian delegation to Saudi Arabia recently,
according to the Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Public Sector Minister Atef Obied, who headed the delegation,
told reporters here today that the biggest agreement involves
setting up a joint holding company with a capital of 500 million
dollars to invest in tourism, construction and factories in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Two other joint companies were agreed upon to produce steel and
glass, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
